<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Akayev Creates 4 New Major Generals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Akayev Creates 4 New Major Generals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1905141594 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 19 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1905141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report under "From Our Correspondents and News </F>
Agencies" rubric: "Kirghizia [Kyrgyzstan] Has 25 Generals for 
15,000 Servicemen"] 
  [Text] Exercises by the Armed Forces of Kirghizia held 
the other day were marked by a shower of stars on commanders' 
shoulder boards. 
  By an edict of President Askar Akayev, four Kirghizian Army 
officers were simultaneously promoted to the rank of major 
general. Competent sources in the Defense Ministry claim that 
the Republic, whose Armed Forces number barely 15,000, now has 
22 serving majors general and three lieutenants general. True, 
the actual commander in chief, President Akayev, holds the 
modest rank of reserve colonel. 

</TEXT>

