<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   General on Deteriorating Afghan Border Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General on Deteriorating Afghan Border Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905202294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1616 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The situation on the Tajik-Afghan border has been 
deteriorating over the past seven days, Chief of the Collective 
Peacekeeping Forces' Staff Colonel-General Grigoriy Bessmertniy 
told INTERFAX in an exclusive interview on Thursday [19 May]. 
  He said that due to general warming the high-mountain passes 
have become easily accessible to the opposition militants and 
that Tajik opposition military formations daily shell border 
posts from the rear and from Afghanistan. Attempts to cross the 
border have also become more frequent, he said. 
  He announced that on Thursday morning, footprints of about 
40 
people who had penetrated into Tajikistan had been discovered in 
the section controlled by the Khorog border-guard detachment. 
"The trespassers have not be found yet," he said. 
  Bessmertniy believes that preparations for the Muslim 
sacrifice festival, marked on 20 May, is containing a 
large-scale offensive by Tajik militants. 
  He also noted that the situation was particularly serious in 
the section running along the Ishkashim, Khorog, and Kalaikhum 
regions of the Gorno-Badakhshan Autonomous Region. The 
peacekeeping forces are not strong enough to block the mountain 
passes and roads linking Afghanistan and Tajikistan. 
  Although Kazakhstan signed the agreement on participation in 
the peacekeeping forces twice -- on September 24, 1993 and on 
April 15, 1994 -- it has not yet sent in its contingent, said 
Bessmertniy. 
  He announced that according to border guards, the armed 
opposition is concentrating forces in the Ishkashim direction. 
These forces are extremely mobile, well-prepared for warfare in 
the mountains, are equipped with the most up-to-date 
radio-communication equipment, know the terrain very well and 
have guides. 
  He said that no attempts had been made lately to start talks 
with the armed opposition, as was done last winter. He also 
said that the peacekeeping forces were ready to participate in 
the inter-Tajik talks, which, he said, would only benefit the 
parties concerned. 
  He said that the armed opposition was accumulating forces 
and 
armaments. "Only Allah knows what will happen in this region in 
the near future. Judging by all accounts, the situation on the 
Tajik-Afghan border will deteriorate," said Bessmertniy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

