<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Sure Baku To Sign Cease-Fire Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Sure Baku To Sign Cease-Fire Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1905081794 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 19 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK1905081794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report Yuriy Golotyuk in the "Nagorno-Karabakh" column: </F>
"The Cease-Fire Agreement May Be Signed After All. Everything 
Depends on the Azerbaijani Side"] 
  [Excerpt] As Armenian presidential aide Levon Zarubyan 
told SEGODNYA's correspondent yesterday, so far there is still a 
hope that the Azerbaijani side within the next few hours or days 
will sign an accord for a cease-fire in Karabakh and on military 
and technical aspects of disengagement of the warring sides. 
Because Russia, Armenia, and Nagorno-Karabakh have actually 
signed this document already, the accord will automatically come 
into effect. The presidential aide refused to say in how many 
days in this event Russian peace-keeping troops will appear in 
Karabakh, pointing out that "the document's details are 
confidential." 
  Mr. Zarubyan stated that the proposed option for a Karabakh 
settlement "is generally very favorable to Armenia because it 
essentially attests to its military victories, whereas for 
Azerbaijan it highlights its military failures." The Armenian 
presidential aide suggested this was the reason for Azerbaijan's 
unwillingness to sign the accord. 
  Other officials in Yerevan and Stepanakert yesterday 
refrained from comment on the results of a Moscow meeting 
between the defense department chiefs of Armenia, Azerbaijan, 
and Nagorno-Karabakh. On his return to Yerevan, Armenian 
Defense Minister Serzh Sarkisyan only stated the following, "God 
knows: Whether or not the Azerbaijanis will sign this document 
does not depend on us." He also voiced confidence that "the 
agreement will still be signed in the very near future." The 
diplomatic department is pinning serious hopes on a visit to 
Baku by Vladimir Kazimirov, the Russian president's special 
envoy, for talks on a settlement in Nagorno-Kazabakh. Yerevan 
believes that Mr. Kazimirov will possibly manage to sway the 
Azerbaijani side. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

