Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Comments by President's Representative </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Comments by President's Representative </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1905114494 Yerevan ARAGIL ELECTRONIC NEWS BULLETIN in 
English 0744 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1905114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan ARAGIL ELECTRONIC NEWS BULLETIN </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yerevan ("AZG" daily), 05/19/94 -- "Armenia greets 
and appreciates the heavy burden of a disengager, which Russian 
Federation took," said acting spokesman of the President Levon 
Zurabyan regarding the recent meeting of Defense Ministers in 
Moscow. The Azeri delegation didn't sign the agreement for some 
reasons, and left for Baku to continue discussions. 
Nevertheless, the atmosphere of the Moscow meeting was such 
that the sides were close to a peaceful resolution of the 
conflict. "The fact is, there is no military euphoria neither 
in Mountainous Karabakh nor in Azerbaijan today," Zurabyan said. 
  Presidential spokesman considered a success the fact that 
Mountainous Karabakh was recognized as an equal side for the 
first time, and fully participated in negotiations. 
  Regarding the document, developed in Moscow on 17 May, 
Zurabyan said that its essence was in coordination of 
military-technical aspects of the cease-fire. It gives details 
about implementation of the cease-fire, the limits, to which the 
Azeri and RMK [Republic of Mountainous Karabakh] troops must be 
withdrawn, defines the order of stationing the observers, which 
will include military representatives of Russia, Armenia, 
Mountainous Karabakh, Azerbaijan, as well as CIS and CSCE member 
countries. "Armenia pays great importance to the CSCE 
participation in the observers mission and believes, this will 
significantly strengthen stability of the cease-fire," said 
Levon Zurabyan. Moscow meeting prepared a new agreement, called 
"An agreement on stopping the military conflict and eliminating 
its consequences," which will be signed on a highest level. The 
agreement stipulates withdrawal of armed forces from occupied 
territories, lifting the blockade and return of refugees. 
According to Zurabyan, this agreement will open the way for 
discussing the RMK status within the CSCE framework. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

