<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma To Consider Financial Concessions for Media </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma To Consider Financial Concessions for Media </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1905104794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 19 May 94 
First Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1905104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report from ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA, ITAR-TASS </F>
column under the "Yesterday, Today, Tomorrow" rubric: "Press 
Will Not Survive Without Concessions"] 
  [Text] "The only way of preventing an information vacuum 
is to provide the Russian mass media with tax, financial, and 
customs concessions." 
  Federation Council Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko voiced that 
opinion at a meeting with journalists yesterday. As you know, 
he has sent the State Duma a draft law "On State Protectionism 
Toward the Russian Mass Media" by way of a legislative 
initiative. 
  Vladimir Shumeyko believes that all the mass media, apart 
from promotional and erotic publications, should be exempt from 
profits tax. The draft law that he is proposing contains the 
following stance: "The editorial offices of mass media, 
publishing houses, printing enterpries, television and radio 
companies, news agenices, and a number of other organizations 
'are not liable to value added tax, tax on enterprises' land and 
property, or profit tax in respect of the proportion payable 
into the federal budget.'" 
  The government has sent a similar law to the State Duma. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

