<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Russia International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Official on Moscow Partnership Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Official on Moscow Partnership Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905181394 Moscow RIA in English 1347 GMT 19 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1905181394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, May 19, RIA -- "Russia's cooperation with 
NATO should be in line with its possibilities and intentions," 
NATO information department chief Francois Vilaneque told RIA. 
Commenting on Moscow's intentions to win a special status in 
relations with NATO, he compared the Partnership for Peace 
Programme with a restaurant in which every visitor chooses a 
dish to his or her taste. "Russia is a client like any other," 
said the department chief, "on accepting the programme, it has 
every right to build and develop its relations with NATO as 
believes most useful for her." 
  The NATO session in Brussels this week confirmed its former 
position: The Partnership for Peace Programme includes standard 
principles for all states joining it and cannot grant advantages 
to anybody. Having accepted its principles, every country 
chooses forms and volume of its individual participation in 
accordance with its wishes and capacities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

