<H3> <TI>   RSA-Russia Diamond Contract Reconsidered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSA-Russia Diamond Contract Reconsidered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1905130294 London FINANCIAL TIMES in English 19 May 94 p 
2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PM1905130294 </F>
<F P=104>  London FINANCIAL TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kenneth Gooding in London and John Lloyd in </F>
Moscow: "De Beers in Russian Diamond Accord"] 
  [Text] De Beers of South Africa stepped back from a 
potentially serious conflict yesterday by agreeing to consider 
changes to its $5bn (3.3bn pound) diamond marketing contract 
with Russia. 
  At the same time the Russian government representatives 
agreed "to take necessary steps" to stop rough (uncut) diamonds 
leaking from Russia through unofficial channels to the west 
where they threatened to destabilise the market. 
  Trade sources suggested that, after the Russians were 
publicly rebuked by De Beers in December for breaking the 
contract, the flow of unofficial diamonds eased but recently it 
had been increasing again. 
  There were sighs of relief in the diamond trade yesterday 
because Russia supplies about 25 per cent of the diamonds De 
Beers sells through its London-based Central Selling 
Organisation [CSO]. The CSO controls more than 80 per cent of 
the world's trade in rough diamonds. 
  In 1990 De Beers lent Russia $1bn, shipped some of the 
Russian stockpile to London as collateral and signed the 
five-year marketing agreement. This permits Russia to sell 5 
per cent of its rough diamond output directly to the west for 
"market testing". 
  While there are no indications that Russia wished to end the 
contract with the world's most successful cartel, some officials 
have been pressing for the federation to keep a bigger share. 
Mr Yevgeniy Bychkev, head of Komdragment, the Russian diamond 
and precious stones committee, who was in the Russian 
negotiating team this week, is demanding that Russia be able to 
keep 25 per cent of its rough diamond trade. 
  The De Beers team was headed by Mr Nicholas Oppenheimer, its 
deputy chairman and chairman of the CSO. According to diamond 
trade sources he stepped in at the last moment because 
relationships had become strained. 
  Mr Gary Ralfe, who negotiated the Russian contract and 
publicly castigated Russia for breaking it, was previously 
expected to head the De Beers team. He was in Moscow with Mr 
Oppenheimer, however. Mr Richard Wake-Walker, previously De 
Beers' representative in Moscow, quit the group recently after 
being replaced by Mr Ray Clark. The Diamantaire trade 
newsletter suggested Mr Wake-Walker "advocated a flexible 
negotiating strategy with Russia while Mr Ralfe and Mr Clark 
appear to be taking a tough, no-concessions approach". 
  The large delegation with which Russia faced Mr Oppenheimer 
included representatives from the Sakha diamond-producing 
region, as well as the Russian diamond committee and the 
Ministries of Finance and Foreign Economic Affairs -- among whom 
the right approach is still being debated. Russia's need for 
increased income from exports has been aggravated by the recent 
fall in the oil price, its main export earner -- and by the 
virtual disappearance of its manufactured goods from the world 
market. 
  A joint communique yesterday said "the parties remain 
committed to the existing agreement, pending their agreeing on 
any modification. They are also committed to the stability of 
the international diamond market and to taking the necessary 
steps to curtail Russian rough gem diamonds reaching the market 
outside the current marketing arrangements." 

</TEXT>

