<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pacific Fleet Explosion Result of Failed Theft </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pacific Fleet Explosion Result of Failed Theft </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905194794 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" program] </F>
  [Text] The procuracy of the Pacific Fleet has established 
the reasons for the vast explosion at the fleet's aviation 
(bomb) store. According to the procuracy, one of the servicemen 
learnt that some of the things stored at the dump contained 
precious metals and decided, with his friends, to remove them. 
They found the munition they were seeking and began to dig into 
it with a bayonet. When the munition unexpectedly burst into 
flames the soldiers could think of nothing better to do than to 
run away. 
  As a result of the subsequent fire and explosion about 200 
wagon-loads of munitions went up into the air and great material 
damage was caused to the neighboring villages. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63140 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov098_d_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Maritime Kray To Review Arms Depot Location After Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Maritime Kray To Review Arms Depot Location After Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905133594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1124 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The administration of the Maritime Territory (the 
Far East) is to review the location of arms depots, Vice 
Governor Valentin Dubinin told Interfax on Thursday. 
  This decision was taken after an explosion on the arms depot 
in Novonezhino, not far from Vladivostok, on May 14, which 
inflicted serious damage on the neighboring villages. 
  Dubinin also stated that the Novonezhino depot would be 
eliminated and that he opposed he idea of turning the Maritime 
Territory into an "arms graveyard" (a large part of the 
ammunition stored in Novonezhino was produced in the 1940s). 
  Commenting on the dismissal of Pacific Fleet Commander 
Georgiy Gurinov following the explosion, Dubinin said that this 
move would hardly influence discipline on the Pacific Fleet. 
"The government must pay servicemen on time and as much as they 
need. How can one talk about discipline when servicemen do not 
receive their salaries for months?" he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

