<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Sums Up Results of Illegal Fishing Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Sums Up Results of Illegal Fishing Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005054194 Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network in Russian 0715 GMT 14 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2005054194 </F>
<F P=104>  Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Pacific Ocean" Program] </F>
  [Text] The first stage of Operation Putina has been 
completed. The aim of the operation was to protect Russian 
economic interests in its territorial waters. In other words, 
to combat illegal fishing. Border troops; officials from the 
Ministry of Internal Affairs, the Customs, the Taxation Police, 
Primorrybvod [Maritime Kray Fishery Department], Sakhalinrybvod 
[Sakhalin Fishery Department]; and naval personnel took part in 
the operation. Captain First Rank Aleksey Velikanov, deputy 
chief of the Pacific Border District Maritime Department, tells 
us about the results of the first stage of Operation Putina. 
  [Begin Velikanov recording] The first stage of Operation 
Putina '94 ended on 10 May. The results are as follows: During 
the operation, more than 800 vessels, of which nearly 300 were 
foreign, were found in Russian territorial waters and exclusive 
economic zone. One hundred and fifteen [Russian] and 24 foreign 
vessels were inspected. Twenty [Russian] and four foreign 
vessels were cited for breach of fishing regulations. The 
offending [Russian] vessels were fined more than 200 million 
rubles. The Japanese fishing vessel was fined $15,385 and 
fishing permits of the three remaining foreign vessels were 
revoked. Losses estimated at approximately 20 billion rubles 
were averted through the resources of those who took part in the 
operation. Various resources, namely the Pacific Border 
District, the Pacific Fleet, Primorrybvod, Sakhalinrybvod, the 
Environment Protection Committee, Spetsmorinspektsiya [Special 
Maritime Inspection], as well as the Pacific Fleet and Border 
District aviation took part in the operation. 
  The next stage of the operation is planned for the latter 
part of June. However, this does not mean that in the interim 
the security of the exclusive economic zone and the state border 
will be relaxed. Already, the customs and border troops in 
Korsakov, Sakhalin Oblast, early this morning detained two 
vessels engaged in the illegal transfer of crabs. They are both 
currently under investigation. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

