<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian-Brokered Cease-Fire on Karabakh Border Persists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian-Brokered Cease-Fire on Karabakh Border Persists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905130694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1214 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondents Vadim Byrkin and </F>
Tigran Liloyan] 
  [Text] Stepanakert-Yerevan 19 May TASS -- The situation on 
the borders of Nagorno-Karabakh remains quiet on Thursday [19 
May]. Masis Mailyan, adviser to the Nagorno-Karabakh Foreign 
Ministry, told ITAR-TASS on Thursday that the observance by the 
conflicting parties of a ceasefire understanding is a result of 
the Moscow meeting of the defence ministers from Armenia, 
Azerbaijan and Nagorno-Karabakh, which was reached with the 
mediation of Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev. 
  Mailyan added that the cease-fire is a good prerequisite for 
Azerbaijan to join an understanding on the order of realising 
the Moscow protocol of last 18 February. 
  The adviser noted that the Karabakh military leadership 
returned to Stepanakert on Wednesday evening and expects 
Azerbaijan to join a protocol on ceasefire and disengagement of 
sides in the zone of the Armenian-Azeri conflict, which was 
signed by Armenia, Nagorno-Karabakh and Russia in Moscow on 17 
May. 
  According to information from the Armenian Defence Ministry 
press service, last night and this morning were quiet on 
Armenian borders. The sides refrain from firing engagements and 
active combat operations. 

</TEXT>

