<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Not Yet Ordered To Withdraw From Inguri River </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Not Yet Ordered To Withdraw From Inguri River </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1805130694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1114 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1805130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Georgian Army has not as yet been ordered to 
withdraw its troops from the line of conflict with the Abkhazian 
formations along the Inguri River in order to create a security 
zone. This was announced to INTERFAX by Georgian Defense 
Minister Lieutenant-General Varden Nadibaidze today. 
  The Georgian-Abkhazian agreement signed in Moscow on 14 May 
says that international observers and a CIS peace-keeping 
contingent mostly composed from the Russian forces will come to 
this security zone after the conflicting parties withdraw their 
troops 12 km away from the Inguri River. There will be 2,500 or 
3,000 servicemen in the CIS peace-keeping forces. 
  Nadibaidze stated that the Georgian Army would carry out all 
orders received from the commander-in-chief and Georgian leader 
Eduard Shevardnadze. 
  However, Chief of the Russian Transcaucasian Troops Group 
press center, Colonel Gennadiy Dolgachev, said in an interview 
with INTERFAX that the peace-keeping contingent was likely to be 
formed from the Russian Transcaucasian troops. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

