<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliamentary Opposition Opposes Accords on Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliamentary Opposition Opposes Accords on Abkhazia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905131994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1124 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the session of parliament in Georgia on Thursday 
[19 May]. Opposition parties again demanded to disavow the 
agreement on cease-fire and the disengagement of troops, which 
was signed in Moscow on 14 May following the results of the 
Georgian-Abkhazian talks. The document envisages the withdrawal 
of the Georgian and Abkhazian units from the line of 
confrontation passing along the Inguri River, the deployment in 
the "buffer zone" of peacekeepers. The opposition believes that 
the materialization of the document will lead to the loss of 
Abkhazia. 
  Deputy Irakly Tsereteli demanded that question be raised on 
confidence to the head of state Eduard Shevardnadze. If this is 
not done before 26 May, Day of Independence, he said, people 
will do this, instead of parliament. 
  The argument caused by the signing by Georgia of an 
agreement 
on the settlement, nearly broke the session of parliament on 
Tuesday. 
  Commenting in an interview with INTERFAX on the demands to 
hold early parliamentary elections, leader of the Republican 
Party, Ivlian Khandrava said that he did not see any legitimate 
mechanism for holding them. 
  The only way, he said, is the consent of two-thirds of the 
current parliament which is impossible to obtain. All the rest 
steps, including referendums and decisions by the head of state 
would not be legitimate, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

