<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resolution Issued on Arms Traders Seeking Foreign Partners </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resolution Issued on Arms Traders Seeking Foreign Partners </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905221394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1927 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian government has, in a bid to improve 
cooperation with western nations in arms sales, passed a 
resolution granting manufacturers of arms and military hardware 
the right to seek foreign partners independently and sign 
contracts with them for the export of their surplus products 
after meeting the government order. 
  Moscow has thereby virtually eliminated the Rosvooruzheniye 
concern's monopoly of the arms trade. The concern was set up at 
the end of last year and, according to Russian Vice-Premier and 
Economics Minister Aleksandr Shokhin, should have become a 
"holding of other organizations currently involved in arms 
trading." However, leading arms designers and manufacturers 
objected to the formation of the concern, seeing in it a threat 
to the new arms export mechanism created after the break up of 
the USSR. 
  Under the new government resolution, arms exporters must 
prove their suitability to engage in foreign trade and be 
registered accordingly. They negotiate and pass tactical and 
technical specifications for certain types of arms and military 
hardware to partners from countries with which arms trade is not 
prohibited. Arms manufacturers also have the right to select 
agents from a list of organizations which have permission to 
engage in foreign trade in arms. 
  Russian arms exports have fallen in recent years from 
approximately 10 million dollars to approximately 2.2 million 
dollars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

