<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov on Minister Helping Solve Chechen Problem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Filatov on Minister Helping Solve Chechen Problem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905165294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1335 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian president's chief of staff, Sergey 
Filatov, said that, with Nikolay Yegorov's appointment as 
minister of the affairs of nationalities and regional policy, 
Russia would resolve its disputes with its separatist republic 
of Chechnya much sooner. 
  "We are concerned about the crime problem and the position 
of 
the poor in that republic," Filatov told Interfax correspondent 
Vyacheslav Terekhov on Thursday. "It's not the status of 
Chechnya or any legal matters that we are concerned about but 
the maintenance of peace around Chechnya," which is being 
threatened today by tension between Chechnya and another Russian 
republic, Dagestan, he said. 
  "We would like to preclude further impoverishment and even 
lower living standards in Chechnya. Those matters are giving 
President Boris Yeltsin a lot of concern," Filatov said. 
  Yegorov replaces Sergey Shakhray, recently dismissed by 
Yeltsin as minister of the affairs of nationalities and reginal 
policy. 

</TEXT>

