<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communications Satellite Launched From Baykonur </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communications Satellite Launched From Baykonur </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005050694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0501 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005050694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by itar-tass string correspondent semyon ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 20 -- A Gorizont communications and 
telecasting satellite was launched from Site 81 of the Baykonur 
Cosmodrome at 05.01, Moscow Daylight Saving Time, on Friday by 
Russian Space Defence Forces (SDF). 
  The satellite was lofted into space atop a heavy-duty 
three-stage Proton-K booster rocket with a Dm-2 boost section. 
  This is the second Gorizont satellite launched under a 
contract between Russia and the U.S. Rimsat company (the first 
one was launched on November 18, 1993). 
  The contract provides for the launching of seven Russian 
satellites -- three Gorizont ones and four Express ones -- 
within the period of September 1993 to March 1996. They are put 
into geostationary orbits with fixed postions over the Pacific 
Ocean region. The full value of the contgract is 150 million 
U.S. dollars. 
  The successful launch was watched by Rimsat company 
representatives, a spokesman at the SDF press centre told 
ITAR-TASS. 
  The launch was the 210th one since 1967 when a Proton-K 
booster rocket was used for the first time and the 188th 
successful one. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63190 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov098_b_94030" </HT>


