<DOCNO> FBIS4-63191 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov098_b_94031" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Cites Yeltsin's Fears Over Defense Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Cites Yeltsin's Fears Over Defense Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905164994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1335 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Presidential spokesman Vyacheslav Kostikov quoted 
Yeltsin as saying that the administration did not believe the 
Duma-approved 37 billion rubles defence budget was adequate 
enough to meet all of the Army's outstanding requirements. 
However, despite verbal declarations of sympathy with the 
Russian Army's hardships, it was this budget that opposition 
parties such as Liberal Democrats, Communists and others had 
approved in its first reading, Kostikov said. 
  In his words, there is a ploy behind the parliamentary move 
aimed to put the Army on a ration so as to bring it into head on 
collision with the president. "The president is well aware of 
this behind-the-scenes political gambling". 
  On the country's further defence spending, Kostikov said 
that 
it would make no sense to increase military expenditure given 
that the Russian Army was to be trimmed down. But to try to 
keep it at last year's level proceeding from the 1993 prices was 
a different matter altogether, Kostikov said. 
  However, he made it clear that an increase in this year's 
defence budget would not be made at the cost of public spending. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63192 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov098_b_94032" </HT>


