<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Supports Moderate Arms Spending Rise </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Supports Moderate Arms Spending Rise </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905124694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1141 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 19 TASS -- The Russian president stands 
for preserving the defence budget at the last year's level in 
comparable prices, without precluding its possible moderate 
growth, presidential press secretary Vyacheslav Kostikov told a 
briefing on Thursday in reply to an ITAR-TASS question. 
  However, Boris Yeltsin does not intend to yield to lobbying 
and to permit its sharp rise: such a disbalance is fraught with 
an increase in social tension. 
  The press secretary called attention to the fact that 
"communist-Zhirinovskiy opposition", speaking in words about 
their loyalty to the army, voted at the Russian parliament lower 
house for a minimum defence budget for tactical reasons. 
  According to Kostikov, it wants to give hand-outs to the 
army, causing dissatisfaction there, and to put it at 
loggerheads with the president. 
  Kostikov also expressed the president's concern over the 
continued campaign in some media against Russian Defence 
Minister Pavel Grachev. 
  "The president does not see clearly reasons behind it. There 
are no real grounds to say that there is misunderstanding 
between the president and the defence minister," he stressed. 
  "The president declares his full political and moral support 
for Pavel Grachev. But at the same time, he does not want to 
show that he has no serious claims to the minister," Kostikov 
continued, adding that Yeltsin is not satisfied with progress of 
the military reform. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

