<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Rejects New Army Uniform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Rejects New Army Uniform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1805124494 Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS in Russian 18 May 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK1805124494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The Minister Is Unclothed!"] </F>
  [Text] President Yeltsin has refused to approve the new 
Russian army uniform sported by Pavel Grachev and the entire 
Defense Ministry. Grachev's service jacket has been deemed 
reminiscent of a Latin American dictator's outfit. It is 
noteworthy that Pavel Grachev has worn his uniform illegally. 
Being part of the Russian state trappings, it is subject to 
approval by a special legislative enactment. 
  Several hundred billion rubles has been spent on designing 
the "Grachev-style" uniform. Under the orders of the USSR 
Defense Ministry still in effect, a new uniform, just like any 
other innovation, should have been first tested in a particular 
military unit in what is called "experimental wearing" so as to 
identify and take into account all the shortfalls and wishes by 
the military and then have it approved. This has not been done: 
The new uniform was simply presented to the top brass. 
Emulating their bosses, lower-ranking Defense Ministry 
apparatchiks also donned it. At present yet another new uniform 
is hastily being designed, based on Russian national traditions. 
  Interestingly, the designers of the "Grachev" uniform seem 
to 
have vanished into thin air: no one knows who they are. As 
MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS has learned, Colonel Ivan Prekhno, chief 
of the Uniform Design Department, is about to resign. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

