<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Previews Grachev Visit to Brussels </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Previews Grachev Visit to Brussels </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005104794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0948 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 20 May -- Many aspects of partnerly 
cooperation between Russia and the North Atlantic alliance will 
be decided during Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev's 
forthcoming visit to Brussels, during which he will attend the 
NATO Council meeting. This was stated today by Vitaliy Churkin, 
Russian Federation deputy foreign minister, after talks between 
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and Alain Juppe, French 
foreign minister. 
  Vitaliy Churkin stressed that Russia has not officially 
raised the question of special status for itself in the event 
that it joins NATO's Partnership for Peace program. At the 
moment, consideration is being given to an appropriate way of 
reflecting a special form of relations between Russia and NATO. 
The Russian side believes that these relations will be 
extensive and meaningful. The official name for this program of 
cooperation also has to be decided. The scope of the 
interdepartmental consultations on our side goes far beyond 
anything which the countries of Eastern Europe and the CIS 
states, which have already joined Partnership for Peace, are 
prepared to discuss with NATO. Among other things, Russia's 
nuclear status has to be taken into account, the deputy minister 
said. 
  Vitaliy Churkin described Pavel Grachev's forthcoming visit 
to Brussels as unprecedented. The defense minister will meet 
the 16 ministers of defense of the countries belonging to the 
North Atlantic Assembly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

