<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin, CE Official Discuss Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin, CE Official Discuss Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905221794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1927 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905221794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chairman of the Council of Europe Parliamentary 
Assembly Miguel Martinez was sure that Russia would be admitted 
to the Council of Europe at its session in February, 1995. This 
was stated today at the meeting between Miguel Martinez and 
Russian State Duma Speaker Ivan Rybkin. 
  Martinez recognized that some members of the Council of 
Europe Parliamentary Assembly had certain doubts on admission of 
Russia. He stressed that he was trying to talk three or four 
leading states into supporting the idea. 
  Miguel Martinez emphasized that several stated would regard 
the presence of Russian troops in Estonia and Latvia as an 
obstacle to Russia's admission to the Council of Europe. 
Martinez himself did not see the problem as one of basic 
importance. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev received Miguel 
Martinez on the same day. 
  Kozyrev said that the Russian leadership was attracting much 
of attention to dynamic development of relations with the 
Council of Europe, the Russian Foreign Ministry told Interfax. 
  Kozyrev suggested that adoption of the new constitution and 
the free democratic elections in Russia had solved all 
key-problems related to the admission of Russia to the Council 
of Europe. He hoped that Russia's application for admission 
would be considered timely. 

</TEXT>

