<H3> <TI>   Reportage on French Foreign Minister Juppe's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on French Foreign Minister Juppe's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Juppe Welcomes Special Russian NATO Status </H4>

<F P=102> LD1905221094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1952 
GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905221094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 19 May -- Paris welcomes NATO's readiness to 
provide Russia with a special status in the framework of 
"Partnership for Peace" that would correspond to Russia's 
specific character, Alain Juppe, foreign minister of the French 
Republic, told journalists in Moscow on Thursday. 
  France, he said after his talks with Andrey Kozyrev, 
attaches 
great importance to bilateral cooperation with Russia. We are 
trying to encourage partnership between the Russian Federation, 
on the one hand, and Europe and various European institutions, 
on the other. France would like Russia to join the Council of 
Europe. "We are also pleased with the fact," the French 
minister continued, "that the Atlantic Union is ready to give 
special status to Russia that would correspondent to its 
specific character." 
  Juppe said that during the talks in Moscow the situation in 
former Yugoslavia was discussed. You know that our countries 
have been working a lot together on this problem. A few days 
ago Russia, the United States, and the European Union states 
succeeded in adopting a joint document. One must not slacken 
pressure now--it is necessary to continue together to persuade 
the parties in the Bosnian conflict to end hostilities. 

</TEXT>

