<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian, Kazakh Experts To Discuss Baykonur Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian, Kazakh Experts To Discuss Baykonur Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005092194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0035 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondents Veronika Romanenkova and Semen </F>
Ivanov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 20 May (ITAR-TASS) -- It is planned to hold 
a routine meeting of Russian and Kazakhstan experts at the end 
of May to discuss questions of concluding a treaty on leasing 
the Baykonur complex. But before that, on 20 May, it is 
expected that Oleg Soskovets, Russian deputy premier and 
cochairman of the interstate commission on Baykonur, will visit 
the cosmodrome. 
  Oleg Soskovets will be present at the launching of a Proton 
carrier rocket which is to put into orbit the second Gorizont 
space apparatus under a commercial contract with the U.S. 
company Rimsat. The deputy premier will also acquaint himself 
with the state of affairs at Baykonur. 
  The agreement between the Russian Federation and Kazakhstan 
"On the basic principles and conditions for using the Baykonur 
cosmodrome" signed on 28 March by the presidents of the two 
countries should be ratified by the relevant state bodies of 
Russia and Kazakhstan in the near future. After this, the sides 
must conclude the actual treaty on the leasing; specialists on 
the interstate commission are already working on drawing up the 
treaty. 
  However, the problems in "space" relations beteen Russia and 
Kazakhstan did not end with the signing of the agreement. The 
most acutely disputed issue at present is the size of the rent. 
The agreement sets the rent at $115 million a year. But the 
Kazakh side asserts that this is only the "starting price." In 
reality, Russia should pay $480 million a year for Baykonur. 
The difference between 115 million and 480 million can be made 
up by Russia's allocating to Kazakhstan satellite communications 
systems, the results of studies of Kazakhstan's natural 
resources, and also by training Kazakhstan's specialists in 
space equipment. 
  The Russian specialists are bewildered at such an "arbitrary 
interpretation" of the document. They consider that 115 million 
is the total size of the rent which already includes the price 
of services provided for Kazakhstan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

