<H3> <TI>   Ostankino Broadcasts to Uzbekistan May Be Cut </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ostankino Broadcasts to Uzbekistan May Be Cut </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905221894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1927 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905221894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Well informed sources state that June could see the 
end of the relaying of Ostankino television and Mayak radio to 
Uzbekistan. 
  Zafar Khakimov of the Uzbek national broadcast company would 
neither confirm or deny this information to Interfax saying that 
he did not have the relevant information. 
  In the meantime local television and radio workers have 
already been told that in the near future Uzbek broadcasting 
will be increased by a total of 20 hours per day to make up for 
the loss of Ostankino and Mayak. To this end another 200 people 
will be employed. 
  For Uzbek residents television and radio programs from 
Moscow 
are the main source of information about life in Russia, the CIS 
and the world. Of the former Soviet and now Russian newspapers, 
only RABOCHAYA TRIBUNA, TRUD and MEDITSINSKAYA GAZETA are 
published in the republic. 

</TEXT>

