<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Previews Latin American Tour </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Previews Latin American Tour </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905214094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2019 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905214094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Viktor Dmitriyev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 19 TASS -- "I do not share the view that 
Latin America is far from Russia's foreign policy interests", 
the speaker of the Russian parliament's upper house, the 
Federation Council, said on Thursday. 
  Vladimir Shumeyko met with newsmen ahead of an official 
visit 
by a Federation Council delegation to Latin America, which is 
due to start on Sunday. During the tour, the Russian delegation 
will visit Chile, Argentina, Brazil, Venezuela and Ecuador. 
  According to the speaker, Russia can profit considerably by 
using the experience of democratic consolidation in Latin 
American countries. 
  In particular, he said, has gone through processes in its 
development very similar to those underway in Russia, namely a 
transition from early democracy to authoritarian rule, then to 
renewed democracy and market relations. 
  Shumeyko also believes that Argentina has one of the most 
perfect civil codes on peace, which proves to mature democracy 
in this South American country. Apart from this, Argentina has 
already achieved national accord, which Russia is seeking at the 
moment. 
  The present-day Russia is not guided by ideological 
considerations when choosing its partners, the Federation 
Council speaker noted. The main motivation is just mutually 
beneficial contacts. The potential foe such contacts with Latin 
American countries is enormous, and they should be certainly 
stepped up. 
  Shumeyko confirmed his profound respect for Cuban leader 
Fidel Castro. "During my visit to Cuba, I had three-hour talks 
with Fidel, which showed that his assessment of the current 
political and economic situation, as well as of the global 
processes, has very little to do with its interpretation by the 
mass media", the speaker stressed. "Politicians of this level 
should not be spoken about in passing. Fidel Castro is the 
world's property, and I will never go back on my words". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

