<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finnish Businessmen Optimistic on President's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finnish Businessmen Optimistic on President's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2005110194 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 20 May 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2005110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Pavel Shinkarenko report under the "Visits" rubric: "Boris </F>
Yeltsin and Martti Ahtisaari Have `Coordinated Positions.' The 
Finnish President's First Official Visit to Moscow Ended 
Yesterday"] 
  [Text] At a dinner in honor of the eminent Finnish guest, 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin noted that the present leaders 
of Russia and Finland not only value the positive undertakings 
of their predecessors but also "intend to build on them." It 
was thus stressed that Russo-Finnish relations are a 
"significant factor for stability in northern Europe and the 
Baltic region," and consequently it is necessary to "constantly 
coordinate positions." 
  As ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI has learned, no joint documents were 
signed on the basis of the results of the talks. But the fact 
that President Ahtisaari was accompanied on his trip by a large 
group of Finnish entrepreneurs is indicative. The two 
countries' businessmen did not waste time on protocol matters 
but sought to use the top-level talks to consolidate their 
economic positions in Russia. Especially since both President 
Yeltsin and President Ahtisaari regarded with approval the 
development of direct contacts not only between state 
enterprises but also at the level of private firms. The figures 
are as follows: In 1993 Russo-Finnish trade turnover was more 
than 40 percent up on the previous year and totaled almost $2.5 
billion. Furthermore, cooperation is developing not only at 
state level but also between firms and individual enterprises. 
Finnish companies are showing greatest activeness in Russia's 
border regions -- St. Petersburg, Karelia, and Leningrad and 
Murmansk oblasts. Special energy-saving and rational forestry 
use programs have been prepared for those regions. Projects for 
the development of mobile radio telephone systems, the 
modernization of highways and railroads, ports, and border 
transport crossings are being developed. A program of 
cooperation in the assimilation of oil and gas deposits in the 
northern regions of Russia is justn one of those being prepared. 
  It is to be presumed that President Ahtisaari's visit to 
Moscow and his talks with Boris Yeltsin and Viktor Chernomyrdin 
will give fresh impetus to mutually beneficial cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

