<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Exclusive' Interview With Crimean President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Exclusive' Interview With Crimean President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905194594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1830 
GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905194594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 19 May -- "The Ukrainian leadership is 
making attempts to destabilize the situation in the Crimea, 
provoke a conflict, and use it as an excuse for disrupting the 
presidential elections in Ukraine. By doing this, the present 
leadership in Kiev is trying to stay in power," Crimean 
President Yuriy Meshkov said in an exclusive interview with 
ITAR-TASS this evening. 
  According to him, the Ukrainian leadership had made an 
attempt to eliminate presidential power in the Crimea in the 
past, and on 19 May, Leonid Kravchuk by his decrees reorganized 
the Crimean power ministries. These moves by Kiev, Yuriy 
Meshkov thinks, might seriously aggravate the situation in the 
republic. 
  In his opinion, the redeployment and increased activity of 
the Ukrainian Armed Forces units have been noted on the 
peninsula's territory. Thus, on the night of 18 May, an 
aircraft carrying Valentyn Nedryhaylo, the first deputy interior 
minister, and a special purpose group, secretly arrived in 
Simferopol where they attempted to seize the republic's Interior 
Ministry. 
  Yuriy Meshkov said that on 19 May the Crimean Supreme 
Council 
approved the ministers of internal affairs, security service, 
and justice and, in his opinion, this will make it possible to 
guarantee peace and order in the republic. "If need be," he 
said, "we have enough forces and equipment to prevent the 
situation from getting out of control." 
  The Crimean president also said that, in order to guarantee 
stability, he was prepared to accept compromise decisions but 
not at the expense of Crimean statehood. In particular, Yuriy 
Meshkov said, at his request the Supreme Council suspended the 
discussion of restoring the Crimean Constitution of 6 May 1992. 
  Yuriy Meshkov also told ITAR-TASS that he had accepted the 
proposal by Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk to send a 
delegation of Crimean deputies to Kiev to discuss issues of 
mutual interest. 
  In the opinion of Yuriy Meshkov, in the evolved situation 
Russia should not allow Ukraine to resort to taking inadequate 
measures against the Republic of Crimea. 

</TEXT>

