<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Envoy Denies Coup Allegations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukraine Envoy Denies Coup Allegations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905171894 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1500 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Speaking at the session of the Crimean parliament 
today, Valeriy Kuznetsov, the new interior minister, described 
Kiev's actions as an attempted coup d'etat. 
  In his turn, Vladimir Kryzhanovskiy [Volodymyr 
Kryzhanovskyy], Ukrainian ambassador to Russia, commented on the 
developments in Crimea of last night and today as follows: 
  [Begin Kryzhanovskiy recording] What coup can they be 
talking 
about in the Crimea? A parliamentary session is being held 
there today, it is working calmly and taking decisions which may 
be right, or not quite right, or wrong. You know, special 
purpose troops can be sent to any part of Ukraine at any time -- 
but do I, as an ambassador, need to know about these things? 
Crimea is Ukrainian territory in the same sense as 
Ivano-Frankovsk, or Donetsk, or Zhitomir, or Odessa. All right, 
supposing special troops did go there -- so what? Do you think 
I am very much concerned about the movement of a mere 10 or 15 
servicemen from the special troops around Ukraine? All is quiet 
in Ukraine, a session is in progress in Crimea -- so what coup 
d'etat are we talking about? [end recording] 

</TEXT>

