<H3> <TI>   Minister Blames Crimean Conflict on `External Forces' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Blames Crimean Conflict on `External Forces' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905175394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1616 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Oleksandr Yemets, Ukraine's minister for 
nationalities and migration, believes that Ukraine and Crimea 
could find a "common language" were it not for the interference 
of external forces. Speaking in an interview with 
Interfax-Ukraine Thursday the minister, who is in Simferopol, 
also said that it was impossible to predict the influence of 
external forces on the Crimean leadership. 
  Yemets linked the activities of Russian politicians in 
Crimea 
with the fact that "certain Moscow groupings want to control the 
privatization process in Crimea." 
  Yemets said that threats to the constitution and the 
territorial integrity of Ukraine "will also cause us to react 
firmly." 
  "No-one will solve Crimea's problem by political 
adventurism," he said. 
  Yemets stressed that if Ukrainian property or Ukrainian 
citizens in Crimea were threatened by any kind of force, then 
"force will be answered by force." 

</TEXT>

