<H3> <TI>   Crimea `Exacerbating Relations' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimea `Exacerbating Relations' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005090194 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 0500 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Crimean Republic Supreme Council has taken 
another step towards exacerbating relations with official Kiev. 
By a majority vote at its session on 19 May, it approved the 
appointment of General [Volodymyr] Lepikhov to the post of 
chairman of the autonomy's security service. He was nominated 
by President Yuriy Meshkov. The directive on reorganizing the 
Security Service of the Republic of Crimea into the Security 
Service of Ukraine Main Directorate in Crimea, signed by 
Ukrainian Head of State Leonid Kravchuk, has thus been ignored. 
  The [Security Service of Ukraine] press service in Kiev 
emphasizes that the principal aim of the reorganization is the 
need to enhance the centralization of leadership and the 
effectiveness of this service in fighting organized crime in 
Crimea where the scale of it is ever more threatening. 
  The press service at the same time reports via the TV and 
radio agency Novyny [News] that Crimean President Meshkov has 
effectively ignored (?a coded telegram addressed to him) from 
Yevhen Marchuk, head of the Security Service of Ukraine, where 
he is informed that the Security Service of Ukraine Main 
Directorate in Crimea, set up in accordance with Leonid 
Kravchuk's directive, is to remain unchanged in performing its 
functions (?in order to retain effectiveness). 
  The press service also reports that (Valeriy Malikov), 
Security Service of Ukraine first deputy chairman, and a number 
of his staff are now in Simferopol. They are preparing materials 
on the situation with fighting organized crime in Crimea, which 
will be under consideration at the (?next) sitting of the 
Security Service of Ukraine Collegium. 

</TEXT>

