<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Parliament Postpones Independence Vote </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Parliament Postpones Independence Vote </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905191994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1738 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905191994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS and UKRINFORM correspondents] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol/Kiev/Moscow May 19 TASS -- The Crimean 
parliament postponed on Thursday the scheduled vote on 
reintroducing items of a 1992 draft constitution of the Crimean 
Republic which envisaged greater autonomy of the republic from 
Kiev. 
  The decision was taken upon the demand of Crimean President 
Yuriy Meshkov. Later, the president presented his explanations 
for the postponement of the vote to a parliament closed-doors 
meeting. Earlier Meshkov had been repeatedly calling on the 
lawmakers "not to heighten temperature" on the peninsula. 
  Amid mounting tension in the Crimea, Ukrainian President 
Leonid Kravchuk disbanded on Thursday law enforcement ministries 
of the self-style peninsula republic. 
  According to a presidential decree which was signed on 
Thursday, Crimea's Interior Ministry was reorganised into a 
department of the Interior Ministry of Ukraine directly 
subordinated to Kiev. 
  Thus all local police forces with their premises, weapons, 
transport means and other property were made responsible only to 
Kiev. 
  Similar decrees have put under Kiev's control, Crimean 
Security Service and Ministry of Justice making bringing their 
status down to that of departments of respective Ukrainian 
ministries. 
  By these decrees Kravchuk also appointed heads of the 
aforesaid departments. 
  The regional parliament fired back and formally confirmed 
the 
appointment of Valeriy Kuznetsov full-fledged interior minister 
of the Crimea. Earlier he was appointed to the post by Crimean 
President Yuriy Meshkov. 
  Earlier today the Crimea-based Black Sea Fleet reported that 
for the past 24 hours some 1,000 Ukrainian home guards and 
special forces had been dispatched to the Crimea including a 
group of saboteurs now deployed close to Sevastopol, the main 
base of the Black Sea Fleet. 
  In his angry message the Ukrainian president today warned 
the 
Crimean parliament against "the revision of basic principles of 
relations between Ukraine and its integral part -- the Republic 
of Crimea". "The violation of these principles might lead to 
conflict situations and other unpredictable consequences", 
Kravchuk stressed. 
  The Ukrainian president was even more resolute in his 
telephone conversation with President Boris Yeltsin that took 
place later in the day. 
  The Ukrainian president's press service quoted him as saying 
that "Ukraine would take appropriate measures to preserve 
territorial integrity of the state". 
  The Crimean parliament at its closed-doors meeting decided 
to 
postpone until Friday the discussion on reintroducing items of a 
1992 draft constitution of the Crimean Republic which envisaged 
greater autonomy of the republic from Kiev. 
  The lawmakers voted against a proposal to send a delegation 
to Kiev for negotiations with Ukraine's leadership. 
  In retaliation to President Kravchuk's decrees bringing 
Crimean law enforcement bodies under direct control of Kiev, the 
lawmakers appointed Vladimir Lepikhov chairman of the Crimean 
Security Service, and Lyubov Yeliseyeva-Bora minister of justice. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63252 </DOCNO>
