<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Deputies Discuss Restoration of Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Deputies Discuss Restoration of Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005110794 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] We are continuing to follow events in Crimea with 
great attention. The Crimean Supreme Soviet is continung its 
work in Simferopol. Our correspondent Yevgeniy Novikov reports. 
  [Novikov] At the morning session the deputies were addressed 
by Viktor Mirak, deputy chairman of the Crimean Supreme Soviet. 
He said that during the night of 19-20 May there was a 
telephone conversation between [Crimean President] Yuriy Meshkov 
and Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk. Viktor Mirak said that 
no mutual understanding was reached during the conversation. 
Therefore, Yuriy Meshkov asked that the deputies be told that at 
the session it would be expedient to continue discussion of the 
question of restoring the 6 May 1992 Crimean Constitution. 
Meshkov, himself, is not present at the session. According to 
some reports the Crimean president is on a visit to the Kuban 
[Russia's Krasnodar region]. 
  After hearing Viktor Mirak's report, the deputies began 
discussing the question of restoring the Crimean Constitution. 
The Crimean Tatars group announced that it would not take part 
in the voting on restoration of the Crimean Constitution, giving 
as their reasons that this could exacerbate relations with 
Ukraine. Nevertheless, the 1992 Crimean Constitution was 
restored by a majority vote. This Constitution declares the 
Republic of Crimea as an autonomous state constructing its 
relations with Ukraine on the basis of treaties and agreements. 
This decision by the deputies caused a storm of applause from a 
well-attended rally taking place outside the Crimean Supreme 
Soviet building. 
  After a break for dinner, the session will continue its 
work. 
  [Announcer] I would add that a message from Ukrainian 
President Leonid Kravchuk was read at the session. In the 
message the head of state demanded that the Crimean deputies 
should unconditionally implement the provisions of the Ukrainian 
law on delimitation of powers between the bodies of state power 
of Ukraine and the Crimean Republic. 

</TEXT>

