<H3> <TI>   Constitution Decision `Illegal' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Constitution Decision `Illegal' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005144894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1335 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Intensive consultations are under way in Kiev 
following the Crimean parliament's decision to reinstate the 
republic's constitution of May 6, 1992, presidential spokesman 
Nikolay Mikhalchenko told Interfax-Ukraine. 
  "President Kravchuk and Speaker of Parliament Aleksandr 
Moroz 
are meeting to discuss the issue and I hope the president will 
address the deputies today," he said. 
  On Wednesday, Kravchuk said that if Simferopol took a 
decision to bring back its constitution, he would ask the 
Ukrainian parliament to rescind it. 
  Mikhalchenko said that Simferopol's decision was out of line 
with the Ukrainian basic law and therefore, illegal. "The 
decision would lead to the setting up of a confederation in 
Ukraine which is a unitary state," he said. 

</TEXT>

