<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Restoration of Constitution Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Restoration of Constitution Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005113394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1059 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 20 TASS -- The parliament of the Crimea, 
an autonomous republic of Ukraine, voted on Friday to restore 
the Crimean Constitution of May 6, 1992. Votes against it were 
cast only by 14 deputies from the Crimean Tatars," ITAR-TASS has 
learned by telephone from Petr Chernyakevich, the Crimean 
president's aide for military affairs. [no opening quotation 
marks as received] 
  Chernyakevich described the parliament's decision to restore 
the 1992 Constitution as a correct step. "If this decision had 
been blackballed," Chernyakevich said, "the Ukrainian president 
would have obtained additional means to influence the situation 
on the peninsula." 
  Speaking about the current situation in the Crimea, 
Chernyakevich noted that it was on the whole tranquil. In his 
opinion, this was largely due to the mass media, which drew 
public attention to Ukraine's recent steps, which could have 
destabilised the situation in the Crimea. 
  At the same time, Chernyakevich noted that movements and 
redeployment of Ukrainian troops were spotted on the border with 
the Crimean republic. It is reported that the Ukrainians are 
setting up field hospitals and are trying to place Crimean 
defence units under the control of the Ukrainian National Guard. 
  Chernyakevich also expressed anxiety about the Ukrainian 
president's decree to reorganise the Crimean ministries for 
internal affairs, security and justice into departments 
subordinated to the central Ukrainian ministries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

