<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Democrats Prevent Late Parliament Session </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Democrats Prevent Late Parliament Session </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905214694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1927 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Thursday's evening session of the Ukrainian 
parliament failed to take place because around 120 deputies 
refused to register. 
  The deputies, who came from the Rukh, Statehood, Unity and 
center fractions, were protesting the offer of the post of 
deputy speaker to Aleksandr Tkachenko. 
  The left wing Ukrainian Peasants' Party nominated Tkachenko, 
a former agriculture minister, for the post. 
  Rukh leader Vyacheslav Chornovil appealed for deputies not 
to 
register and confer among fractions on their own candidates for 
deputy speaker. 
  The speaker himself, Aleksandr Moroz, said he would give the 
media a list of the names of the deputies who had refused to 
register for the session. Those deputies, he said, were 
obstructing "constructive" work in parliament. 
  Communist leader Petr Simonenko in an interview with 
Interfax 
Ukraine criticized the national democrats, saying that "we have 
come to parliament to work and they are getting in our way." 
  The rebel deputies meeting Thursday evening must present 
their candidates for the post of deputy speaker by Friday's 
morning session of the Supreme Soviet. 

</TEXT>

