<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Aide Urges `Cool' Approach </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Aide Urges `Cool' Approach </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005125194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1120 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "The war of nerves between Kiev and Simferopol was 
doomed to aggravate," a member of Russia's Presidential Council, 
Emil Payn, told Interfax in comments on developments in and 
around the Crimea. 
  According to him, on the one hand, a negative impact on the 
development of events was made by the tough stand taken by the 
Kiev authorities toward the Crimea as a means of consolidating 
the polarized Ukrainian society on the eve of presidential 
elections. On the other, the Crimean leadership showed no 
particular inclination for compromises, being disposed to take 
decisions made by Kiev too nervously, said Payn. 
  According to him, energetic measures designed to cool the 
situation should be taken by the Russian authorities urgently. 
Such steps should be addressed to both Simferopol and Kiev. 
"They must be not threats, but purely diplomatic measures -- 
statements and actions aimed at preventing the conflict from 
further aggravating," Payn said. 
  He drew attention to the one-sided coverage of the 
developments in and around the Crimea by some Russian news 
media, in particular television, whose solidarity with the 
Crimean authorities might stimulate Simferopol's tough stand 
toward Kiev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

