<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Adopts Broadcasting Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Adopts Broadcasting Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905154194 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1100 
GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1905154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>
<F P=105>  Estonian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Riigikogu adopted the broadcasting law today. 
According to this law, Estonian Radio and Estonian Television 
will continue as independent legal entities. The Riigikogu 
concluded that it would be unjustified to merge the two. Both 
Estonian Radio and Estonian Television may broadcast advertising 
material for up to five percent of the day's broadcasts. This 
permission has been given in order to provide them with proper 
funding. 
  The Riigikogu will set up a broadcasting council before 
taking its summer recess. The council will be the top authority 
for both Estonian Radio and Estonian Television. It is expected 
to be set up in June. 
  As recommended by experts, several clarifications were 
included in the broadcasting law. For example, the procedure 
for issuing broadcasting licenses to privately owned 
broadcasting stations has been made more specific. 
  The law adopted today regulates the rights and obligations 
of 
the electronic media, including those on the basis of which 
private radio stations operate in Estonia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63291 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov098_t_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

