<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Denies Deterioration in Ties With Romania </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Snegur Denies Deterioration in Ties With Romania </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005202994 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1700 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2005202994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>
<F P=105>  Romanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Dispatch from Chisinau] </F>
  [Text] Mr. Mircea Snegur, president of the Republic of 
Moldova, denied that relations between the Republic of Moldova 
and Romania have cooled down of late. In an interview granted 
to Radio Free Europe, he said that this idea, which is being 
intensively aired, does not correspond with reality. We will 
squash this idea very soon, President Snegur said. 
  Positively assessing the post-electoral social and political 
situation in the Republic of Moldova, he said that it enabled 
the country's leadership to start a dialogue with the Tiraspol 
authorities. Referring to the issue of granting a special 
status to the rayons on the left bank of the Dniester River, 
President Snegur said that a possible draft bill in this respect 
will take into consideration a decentralization and the 
assignment of functions to local self-administration bodies, but 
within the framework of a single state, the Republic of Moldova, 
with a single constitution and foreign policy and a single Army 
and police force. Mircea Snegur said that the negotiations will 
be difficult, because the Dniester side insists upon the idea of 
federalization or confederalization. He also emphasized the 
need to solve all differences by political means. 
  At the same time, President Snegur reiterated that the 
withdrawal of the 14th Army of the Russian Federation from the 
territory of the Republic of Moldova should not be synchronized 
with the granting of a special legal status to the rayons on the 
left bank of the Dniester. 
  In the aforementioned interview, President Mircea Snegur 
reiterated that, within the CIS bodies, the leadership of the 
Republic of Moldova only participates in the discussion of 
economic problems and does not participate in the discussion of 
military issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

