<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "NEGA Reports" rubric] </F>
  [Text] The Russian-Moldovan talks on the status and 
pullout of the 14th Russian Army called for mid-May have been 
moved back. There are substantial changes in the composition of 
the Moldovan delegation, primarily connected with the 
resignation of its head, Anatoliy Taranu, extraordinary and 
plenipotentiary ambassador of the Republic of Moldova to Russia. 
He is supposed to be replaced by Nicolae Osmochescu, deputy 
foreign minister of the Republic of Moldova and international 
law specialist, who has been asked to lead a group of experts 
from Chisinau at the talks with Tiraspol. 
  The Moldovan delegation decided to make some concessions in 
the latest round of talks. Backing down on its previous demand 
that the Army be withdrawn by 1 July 1994, it suggested that the 
withdrawal be carried through during one or two years. In the 
opinion of Anatoliy Tiranu, it is not ruled out that Moldova 
could decide on even greater concessions: from approving a 
longer duration of the Army's stay on its territory to assigning 
it the status of a military base. 

</TEXT>

