<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Initials Partnership Agreement With EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Initials Partnership Agreement With EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005221094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1932 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005221094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Brussels, 20 May -- Kazakhstan is the second CIS 
state -- following Ukraine -- to have finished drawing up an 
agreement on partnership and cooperation with the European 
Union. This document was initialled in Brussels on Friday [20 
May]. The ITAR-TASS correspondent learned in the Kazakhstan 
embassy that the agreement will be signed by President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan and the European Commission chairman in 
the coming months. 
  The agreement represents a political document encompassing 
diverse forms of cooperation. It lays the basis for development 
of relations between Kazakhstan and the European Union and is 
designed to promote the expansion of bilateral cooperation 
between this Central Asian republic and each of the 12 countries 
of the European Union. This is essentially the first agreement 
between independent Kazakhstan and such a major international 
association as the European Union. 
  Two more joint documents are now being drawn up to regulate 
relations between the sides in individual spheres of 
cooperation, and in particular, in issues relating to power 
engineering and nuclear materials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

