<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investment, Trade Agreements Signed With Switzerland </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Investment, Trade Agreements Signed With Switzerland </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005123794 Almaty KAZTAG in Russian 1535 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty KAZTAG </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [No dateline as received] Franz Blankart, state 
secretary of the Swiss federal department of national economy, 
speaking at a news conference in Bern about the outcome of his 
visit to Almaty, described Kazakhstan as "a fascinating 
country." During his visit agreements on capital investment and 
trade were signed. He welcomed the development of bilateral 
ties. He said that Kazakhstan "offers a promising future for 
foreign investments." 
  Kazakhstan currently buys from Switzerland technology and 
products of the chemical and some industries worth 20 million 
Swiss francs. For its part Switzerland annually buys Kazakh 
products worth 4.3 million Swiss francs. 
  According to the SWISS TELEGRAPH AGENCY, during his visit 
Mr. 
Blankart signed an agreement on the promotion and protection of 
investments and on trade and economic cooperation. Switzerland 
can invest in environmental protection and railroad development 
in Kazakhstan, with attention being paid to the project for 
constructing a railroad from Turkey to China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

