<DOCNO> FBIS4-63319 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_d_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   N. Caucasian Leaders Urge Lifting Abkhaz Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    N. Caucasian Leaders Urge Lifting Abkhaz Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005181494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1712 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Viktor Zhilyakov] </F>
  [Text] Krasnodar May 20 TASS -- Regional heads of North 
Caucasian republics attending a conference in Baku have appealed 
to the Russian president, asking him to lift sanctions against 
Abkhazia. 
  Participants in the conference believe that lifting economic 
sanctions will step up the process of the settlement of the 
conflict in the region. Head of the republics of Adygeya, 
Dagestan, Ingushetia, Kabardino-Balkaria, North Ossetia, 
Karachayevo-Cherkessia, the Krasnodar, Stavropol, Rostov regions 
and South Ossetia took into account that after signing 
agreements with the participation of the Russian Federation 
conditions for normal and stable life are being created in the 
region. A tendency for the restoration of cultural and economic 
ties has been growing. 
  This question was not included in the agenda of the 
conference and was raised in the course of discussions, 
journalists were told after the conference since they were not 
admitted. 
  The conference was attended by Russian Minister for Affairs 
of Nationalities and Regional Policy, Nikolay Yegorov, who 
answered journalists' questions. 
  Participants adopted an address to President Yeltsin in 
connection with his message to the people of the Northern 
Caucasus on the occasion of the 130th anniversary since the end 
of the Caucasian war. The address says that the people of the 
Northern Caucasus accepted Yeltsin's message with gratitude, 
believing that by the mercy of fate the Russian president put 
the last stop to the Caucasian war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63320 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_d_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meeting of Council of N. Caucasian Regions Ends </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meeting of Council of N. Caucasian Regions Ends </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105133894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1219 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Krasnodar May 21 TASS -- The Kalmyk Republic was 
admitted to the membership of the Social-Economic Cooperation 
Association of North Caucasian Republics, Territories and 
Regions at a meeting of this organisation's council which ended 
here on Friday. 
  The meeting was attended by the leaders of all the North 
Caucasian members of the Russian Federation as well as Speaker 
of the Abkhazian Republic Parliament Vladislav Ardzinba, 
President of the Crimean Republic Yuriy Meshkov and Speaker of 
South Ossetian Parliament Lyudvig Chiberov. 
  The meeting was chaired by Nikolay Yegorov, the Russian 
Federation's minister on nationalities and regional policy. 
  The meeting set up a coordination council of the association 
on struggle against organised crime in the economy and terrorism 
in the North Caucasus. It also approved a programme for the 
development of viticulture and wine-making in the region and 
approved the establishment of a regional business centre in 
Stavropol. 
  Later in the day, the leaders of the North Caucasian members 
of the Russian Federation as well as of the Abkhazian and 
Crimean republics held a brief meeting which adopted a statement 
on the 130th anniversary since the end of the Caucasian war. 

</TEXT>

