<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amur Oblast Demarcation Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amur Oblast Demarcation Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005050194 Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks in 
Russian 0605 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2005050194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [G. Kukevich video report; from the "Dalniy Vostok" program] </F>
  [Text] This event is significant not only for the Amur 
Oblast residents, but for all of the state. Up till now, there 
was not a single border marker at the eastern Russian-Chinese 
border, neither at a land nor a river zone. Today, we are 
adopting a practice of organizing state borders that is 
generally accepted in the world. [Video shows interview with A. 
G. Laskov, chief of demarcation group No. 5] 
  [Begin Laskov recording] There are two demarcation groups 
working in our oblast -- Nos. 4 and 5. I can also say that the 
length of the border on the Amur Oblast territory is 1,281 km. 
The demarcation working groups, which are part of the 
commission, started field work in early May last year. We were 
preparing foundations for border markers, and determined their 
topographic coordinates. Now, the new stage is erecting the 
border markers. Overall, our group will erect 48 border markers 
in Amur Oblast, and group No. 4 will erect 50. In other words, 
98 border markers are to be erected in 1994-95. The 
hydrographers group will determine the location of the main 
fairway. Appropriate documents are being drafted on all of 
these points, and the end result of our work is a protocol 
describing the location of the state border line. After this 
work is concluded, the border with China will be as in the rest 
of the civilized world. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

