<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nizhniy Leaders' Resignation Story `Crude Forgery' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nizhniy Leaders' Resignation Story `Crude Forgery' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2005101794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 20 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2005101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Anatoliy Yershov report: "Nizhniy Novgorod Governor </F>
Rumored Dismissed"] 
  [Text] Nizhniy Novgorod -- Over the past few days Nizhniy 
Novgorod newspaper editorial offices and the radio and 
television have been sent on official oblast administration 
notepaper copies of a letter from Governor B. Nemtsov asking the 
Russian president to relieve both him and Ye. Krestyaninov, the 
president's representative in Nizhniy Novgorod Oblast, of their 
duties. 
  The reason for this resignation is that economic reform in 
the oblast has allegedly been a disaster, a wave of 
anti-Semitism is on the rise, and, under these conditions, 
"people must not be fooled any longer...." Whereas before there 
were sometimes rumors about Governor B. Nemtsov's possibly 
transferring to work in Moscow, this time the "resignation 
question" regarding the two oblast leaders has turned out to be 
a crude forgery. 
  IZVESTIYA was told by Ye. Krestyaninov that the appropriate 
organs will now be investigating just who sent these letters to 
the mass media. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

