<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Predicts Armed Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Predicts Armed Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2105071694 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 21 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK2105071694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Pavel Felgengauer report under the "Crimea" rubric with the </F>
general heading: "General Grachev: `If Troops Are Being Pulled 
Up, an Armed Conflict Is Virtually Unavoidable'"] 
  [Text] Russian Defense Minister General Grachev believes 
that the Crimea situation could cause "a serious conflagration. 
If troops are being moved up, an armed conflict is virtually 
inevitable." The Russian Defense Ministry has been receiving 
reports about the concentration of Ukrainian troops in Crimea. 
There are around 400 Ukrainian special-purpose troops in the 
area of the Belbek airport (10 km north of Simferopol); 500 
contract servicemen landed on the cape of Khersones; and 200 
Ukrainian national guards (primarily from Ukraine's western 
oblasts) are on Sevastopol's eastern outskirts (Sukharnaya 
Balka). Reinforcements amounting to another 200 men are also 
expected. 
  Russian intelligence agencies are checking reports that the 
1st Ukrainian Mobile Air Brigade in Bolgrad has been put on full 
alert. Currently the brigade is under the command of General 
Babich (former chief of staff of the 98th Airborne Division). 
General Grachev knows him as "a competent and decisive officer" 
who is "capable of a great deal." 
  Black Sea Fleet units have been ordered to "stop any 
provocations in the most decisive fashion." Presently, 
facilities of the Crimean Internal Affairs Ministry have been 
protected by special-purpose army units and the OMON [Special 
Purpose Militia Detachment] of the Crimean Internal Affairs 
Ministry. 

</TEXT>

