<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Supreme Council Chairman Gives Briefing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Supreme Council Chairman Gives Briefing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105192094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1737 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The chairman of the Crimean parliament said it was 
the duty of the legislature to restore Crimea's constitution of 
May 6, 1992, and thereby put the peninsula's relations with 
Ukraine on the basis of a treaty. "I cannot see any other option 
-- there is simply none," Sergey Tsekov said at a news 
conference in Simferopol on Saturday. 
  He said that, as the legislature discussed the matter, some 
of its members made more drastic proposals, namely for a 
referendum on the status of the peninsula. Restoration of the 
1992 constitution is "the mildest form of relations with 
Ukraine," Tsekov said. 
  Answering a question by Interfax-Ukraine, he said the 
ultimate objective of the Russia Bloc is to make Crimea an 
independent state and then unify it with Russia, although the 
peninsula might be "reunified" with Russia "together with 
Ukraine." 
  "Many of the problems, above all economic ones, can only be 
solved by the integrating Ukraine with Russia," Tsekov said. 
  He said nothing today poses a threat to Ukraine's 
territorial 
integrity. 
  Asked about troop movements in Crimea, Tsekov said, "There 
are such movements, but they are normal routine troop movements. 
No emergency measures have been planned." 
  He ruled out that the Crimean parliament would be dissolved, 
for that, he said, would be illegal. "There are sensible 
people" in Ukraine's leadership, who "will not allow an 
aggravation of the relations with Crimea," he said. 

</TEXT>

