<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Aide Apportions Blame for Crimean Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Aide Apportions Blame for Crimean Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305091294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2109 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2305091294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 May (ITAR-TASS) -- "The vacation season 
in Crimea has begun." This was how Emil Pain, head of the 
conflict forecasting department of the analysis center under the 
Russian president, reacted to an ITAR-TASS report about 29 
Ukrainian armored personnel carriers appearing on the outskirts 
of Simferopol. 
  In an interview with the ITAR-TASS correspondent the analyst 
noted that the situation around Crimea is getting close to a 
critical point. "All the signs of an uncompromising fight for 
the integrity of the state are there. But strong-arm methods in 
taming separatists proved unsuccessful in Azerbaijan, Georgia, 
Moldova, and Serbia alike," Emil Pain said. "But history never 
teaches anything," he noted. 
  Unlike many experts, Emil Pain puts the blame for the crisis 
not only on Ukrainian but also on Crimean politicians. He 
believes it is possible to speak of the "irresponsibility" of 
Yuriy Meshkov's supporters, who could have carried out the 
Crimean authorities' policy without a confrontation with Ukraine. 
  "It was inexpedient to make a decision to change the Crimean 
Constitution on the eve of the vacation season, because its 
success could have improved the economic situation in the 
peninsula," the scientist believes. But he thinks that "Yuriy 
Meshkov seems to have forgotten that Abkhazia's beaches are no 
worse than Crimea's beaches, and that no one would wish to spend 
a vacation in an area of hostilities." 
  The political scientist stated with alarm that most armed 
conflicts have begun with a change in a certain territory's 
political status. "This time there should not be a military 
clash, because the price to pay for it would be not the future 
of Crimea but global security," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63346 </DOCNO>
