<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Reports Kozyrev-Zlenko Letters on Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Reports Kozyrev-Zlenko Letters on Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105163194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1527 
GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 21 May. (ITAR-TASS) -- The Press and 
Information Department at the Russian Foreign Ministry today 
distributed the following report: 
  "On 20 May Ukraine's Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko sent 
the Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev a letter informing 
him of the decision adopted by Crimea's Supreme Soviet to 
restore the constitution of the Republic of Crimea of 6 May 
1992, which he believes could pose a threat to Ukraine's 
internal political stability and cause tension in relations 
between Russia and Ukraine. 
  "The letter underlines that, in the event of a further 
escalation of the situation, Ukraine retains the right to take 
all necessary measures to safeguard unconditionally the state's 
territorial integrity, in accordance with its Constitution and 
law and in observance of the norms of international law. 
  "In a reply message, Kozyrev says that the possibility of 
tension arising in Russian-Ukrainian relations because of Crimea 
cannot but cause concern and he agrees that international legal 
principles should be observed everywhere. But no less important 
is respect for the sovereign will of the peoples, restraint, and 
the need to exclude the use of force. All the problems arising 
between Ukraine and the sovereign republic of Crimea -- as part 
of Ukraine -- should be settled exclusively by political means. 
  "The situation in Crimea confirms once again the need for 
settling as soon as possible the questions of the Black Sea 
Fleet, proceeding from the accords between the presidents of 
both countries. Russia is ready for this, the letter from 
A.V.Kozyrev says in conclusion." 

</TEXT>

