<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Proposes Tatarstan Scenario for Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Proposes Tatarstan Scenario for Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305113494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1108 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 23 TASS -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister 
Sergey Shakhray and President of Tatarstan Mintimer Shaymiyev 
are going to propose to Ukraine and the Crimea to settle their 
dispute like Moscow and Tatarstan did. 
  Shakhray told reporters on Monday that the example of 
Tatarstan can show to the leaderships of Ukraine and the Crimea 
"how it is possible to settle relations between a strong centre 
and a strong region". 
  In Tatarstan secessionist moods were strong until Moscow 
agreed to sign a bilateral share-power agreement with it. 
Kazan, in its turn, agreed to participate in elections to the 
new Russian parliament which failed in the republic mostly 
because the local leadership was against them. 
  "We want to remind the Ukrainian and Crimean leaders that 
relations between Moscow and Kazan could have developed along a 
very bad scenario in their time, but Russian and Tatar leaders 
had common sense enough to embark on the path of compromises and 
concessions", Shakhray said and added that the situation 
"normalised politically and economicaly" after the share-power 
deal between Moscow and Kazan was reached. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

