<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev To Propose Alternative Partnership Plan to NATO </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev To Propose Alternative Partnership Plan to NATO </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005140694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1316 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Palariya] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 20 TASS -- "Russia is interested in a 
more serious and substantial format of relations with NATO than 
the Partnership for Peace program envisions," Russian Defence 
Minister, Army General Pavel Grachev announced today. 
  "This approach, in our view, rules out surprises and 
unilateral measures, especially of military character, in the 
fields in which we must cooperate as closely as possible," 
General Grachev said after his meeting with French Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe. 
  "We will put forth another plan for partnership, which has 
already been approved by the president of Russia," Grachev 
indicated. Its basic principles consist in Russia's joining the 
program with account being taken of its significant role and 
place in the European security system and the United Nations. 
In addition, Russia cannot limit itself to the signing of the 
standard framework document, the minister said. "We shall work 
to prepare a larger-scale program of cooperation between Russia 
and NATO, based on parameters of practical participation in its 
implementation," the Russian minister stressed. 
  These parameters are political partnership, partnership in 
the military and other fields. On their basis, "we shall 
propose drawing up a large-scale program for Russia's 
cooperation with Partnership for Peace. Only if they are 
approved, Russia will be able to sign the NATO program," Grachev 
said. 
  The minister said he would also set out in his report at 
NATO 
headquarters in Brussels on May 24 Russia's views on prospects 
for the development of the European security system. The accent 
will be placed on the need to ensure the leading role of the 
Conference of Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) in the 
process of forming a regional security system for the 
Commonwealth member-states within the collective security 
treaty, as well as on Russia's vision of the main parameters of 
cooperation with the North Atlantic alliance. 
  Grachev reiterated that his main objective was to tell NATO 
about the main provisions of the Russian military doctrine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

