<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev, Juppe Discuss CIS `Flash Points' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev, Juppe Discuss CIS `Flash Points' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005163394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1240 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Palaria] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 20 TASS -- Russian Defence Minister Pavel 
Grachev and French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe who is on a 
visit in Moscow, discussed the situation in "flash points" in 
the Commonwealth of Independent States. 
  Speaking of the Georgian-Abkhazian confrontation, Grachev 
said that the conflict has a trend for expanding, which affects 
Russia's security as well as its vitally important interests in 
the region. 
  The defence minister stressed that Russia has been 
constantly 
playing a mediator's role aimed at settling the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict politically but, regrettably, it 
does this mission single-handed. 
  Neither international peace-making organisation nor members 
of the Commonwealth of Independent States take an active part in 
its settlement. 
  Grachev also said that 2,500-3,000 blue helmets will be 
dispatched to the region in compliance with the agreement on 
ceasefire and disengagement of forces in Abkhazia, signed in 
Moscow on May 14. 
  They will be stationed along the Inguri River on the 
Abkhazian side as well as in the Galskiy district and the 
Kodorskoye Gorge. 
  As for the Armenian-Azeri conflict, Grachev informed Juppe 
of 
the drafted plan for a Karabakh settlement which was signed by 
Russia, Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh in Moscow on May 17. 
  Azeri Defence Minister Mamedrafi Mammadov was recalled to 
Baku on the same day all of a sudden. According to Grachev, 
this was evidently prompted by the aggravation of the situation 
at the republican parliament. 
  At the same time, he did not preclude a chance that this was 
done for political purposes in order to win time and to invite 
the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe to 
participate in a peace mission and to settle the Karabakh 
conflict under its aegis. 
  If the plan for settling the conflict was signed, Grachev 
noted, Russia would dispatch a peace-keeping force to the region 
on May 24. According to the minister, the Azeri defence minister 
is already in Moscow for the second day. 
  In Grachev's opinion, the essence of his arrival is to sign 
the plan for ceasefire and disengagement of the sides in the 
zone of the Armenian-Azeri confrontation by June 1 after some 
allegedly domestic issues are settled by President Geydar Aliyev. 
  Grachev stressed that Russia would not step back on the plan 
in any way. "The plan is very good. It can really bring 
peace," the minister noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63361 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_a_94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Grachev-Juppe Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Grachev-Juppe Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105105394 Moscow 2x2 Television in Russian 0930 GMT 21 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow 2x2 Television </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev met French 
Foreign Minister Alain Juppe at the Russian Defense Ministry 
today. During their conversation the ministers exchanged 
opinions on the problems of settling the situation in the 
Caucasus and Bosnia, as well as Russian participation in the 
American "Partnership for Peace" program. Alain Juppe showed 
most interest in the Russian plan for settling the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict. As Pavel Grachev stated, in 
accordance with the 14 May agreement, 2,500-3,000 Russian 
peacekeepers will be sent to the conflict zone. They will take 
up positions along the Inguri river, Galskiy Rayon, and the 
Kodorskoye Gorge. 
  Speaking about the prospects for joining the "Partnership 
for 
Peace" program, Pavel Grachev stressed that Russia is not 
demanding special conditions for itself, but believes 
cooperation with NATO countries must not be limited by a 
framework agreement. Therefore at his meeting with NATO 
leadership in Brussels he will put forward a broad package of 
specific proposals on cooperation between Russia and the North 
Atlantic bloc countries in the political and military spheres. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

