<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Says Paris Generally Backs Russian-EU Uranium Deal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe Says Paris Generally Backs Russian-EU Uranium Deal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005191594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1639 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005191594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] France has agreed in principle to accept the 
Shokhin- Brittan formula concerning trade regulations for 
substances used in the nuclear industry, notably uranium, at 
talks between French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and Russian 
officials in Moscow, Interfax was informed by Maxim Medvekov, 
the Russian Foreign Economic Relations Ministry official in 
charge of bilateral cooperation. 
  France was the only EU [European Union] country at a session 
of the EU Council on May 16 not to back the agreements reached 
by Russian Vice-Premier Aleksandr Shokhin and the EU 
Commission's Vice- Chairman Leon Brittan in Moscow on May 2, 
thereby putting the signing of the Agreement on Partnership and 
Cooperation between the EU and the Russian Federation in June or 
July this year under question. 
  Shokhin and Brittan agreed that general trading standards 
would apply to uranium and other fissile substances, but with 
some exceptions. France objected to the formula, but was unable 
to provide any serious arguments to back its objections, 
offering only abstract fears that the European market could 
become inundated by Russian uranium some time in the future. 
  The sides did manage to untie the knot in Moscow, Medvedkov 
said, agreeing on minor technical adjustments to the formula. 
  Now, he said, practically all obstacles to the signing of 
the 
agreement between Russia and the EU in June or July had been 
removed, but he could not be absolutely certain until the draft 
agreement had been approved by the EU Council on June 13. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

