<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev, UK's Hurd Begin Talks in Murmansk </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev, UK's Hurd Begin Talks in Murmansk </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205180794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1725 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov, </F>
Vladimir Novikov] 
  [Text] Murmansk, 22 May -- Russian and British foreign 
ministers began talks here today at the suburban hotel Ogni 
Murmanska. Welcoming the British visitor, Andrey Kozyrev noted 
that the two countries' cooperation during the war was closely 
linked with the port of Murmansk. "We remain allies after the 
ideological blackout that drew our countries apart," he said. 
"We are now returning to the natural state of partnership." 
  "You will be the first foreign minister from another country 
to visit the strategic base of the Russian Navy in Severomorsk," 
Kozyrev went on. "It is very important that the deadly missiles 
are no longer targeted at Britain, same as British Trident 
missiles are no longer targeted at Russia. This too is an 
example of new partnership." 
  The head of the Russian Foreign Ministry also noted that the 
meeting of the two ministers was taking place in a private 
hotel. In his view, this showed that despite all the 
difficulties, the spirit of enterprise had opened itself a way 
in this land of great opportunities. 
  "It is particularly interesting to me to visit Murmansk," 
Douglas Hurd said in his turn. "Older generation Britons, among 
whom I have many friends, went with the convoys across the 
dangerous Arctic waters, threatened by German submarines. This 
was the brightest page in their lives. I am looking forward to 
seeing the city that, among other things, is the administrative 
center of the Russian foreign minister's constituency, and to 
visiting the military base in Severomorsk. The reasons why this 
is important to me lie both in the past and in the present." 
  D. Hurd said he was confident that Murmansk would attract 
large foreign investments because of its vast mineral resources 
and the kray's geographical location. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

