<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Expresses `Concern' With Dalai Lama Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Expresses `Concern' With Dalai Lama Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105093094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1838 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Andrey Lvov] </F>
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 20 May -- In an interview for ITAR-TASS 
today, the Tibetan spiritual leader Dalai Lama, who lives in 
exile in the Indian city of Dhamsala, expressed his hope that he 
would one day return to his homeland. "I hope to return to Lhasa 
at some time, to the Potala palace, the residence of the Dalai 
Lamas," said the former ruler of Tibet, who left Tibet after the 
bloody clashes between the local population and the Chinese Army 
in 1959. 
  The Dalai Lama said he "would find ways and channels to hold 
a referendum on the future of Tibet." He said that in the 
referendum the population would be given the choice of several 
alternatives. One of these is supported by advocates of the 
"middle way" who do not demand the complete separation and 
independence of Tibet from China. The Dala Lama, himself, is 
one of these. A different point of view is held by many young 
Tibetans who insist on complete independence for Tibet. [passage 
omitted] 
  The Dalai Lama stated that the unique Tibetan culture was on 
the verge of disappearing. At the same time he stressed his 
readiness to hold talks with Beijing on the basis of the 
principle that Deng Xiaoping, the architect of Chinese reforms, 
put forward with regard to Taiwan and Hong Kong -- "one 
country-two systems" -- extending it to the present Tibetan 
autonomous region of the PRC. 
  Sharing his impressions about present day Moscow, which he 
has already visited several times, the Dalai Lama said "a lot 
more cars" have appeared on the streets and "many houses are 
under construction near the capital," which in his opinion is 
evidence of development. But a much more striking change is that 
"previously in Moscow it was difficult to communicate with 
ordinary citizens, but now Muscovites converse willingly, they 
ask questions and show a new openness of views and emotions." 
  "I think this is very important," the Buddhist spiritual 
leader stressed. He advised Russians "to create something new 
in the economic sphere" to avoid the drawbacks of the "Western 
economic model." 
  On Saturday the Dalai Lama leaves for Delhi. During his stay 
in Moscow, the PRC embassy in Russia expressed "serious concern" 
about the activity of the Tibetan spiritual leader, which in the 
opinion of Chinese diplomats, was directed "at splitting China." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63373 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_a_94037" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dalai Lama Discusses Future of Tibet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dalai Lama Discusses Future of Tibet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105215594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2045 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105215594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Dmitriy Zlodorev and Andrey </F>
Lvov] 
  [Text] Moscow May 22 TASS -- The Dalai Lama said he will 
find means and ways to hold a referendum on the future of Tibet. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Saturday before his 
departure from Moscow where he was on a three-day visit, the 
Dalai Lama said he remains hopeful that he will return to China 
one day and step into the Tibetan capital of Lhasa and the 
Potala, the former palace of the Dalai Lama. 
  The Dalai Lama fled Tibet after bloody clashes between the 
Tibetan population and Chinese police in 1959 and has been 
living in India ever since. 
  He said that Tibetan culture is on the verge of extinction 
and confirmed his readiness to hold talks with China on the 
basis of the principle "one country -- two systems" proposed by 
architect of chinese reform Deng Xiaoping for Taiwan and Hong 
Kong. He believes this principle could also be applied to Tibet. 
  The Dalai Lama was in Moscow at the invitation of the 
Russian 
Academy of Sciences and the International Foundation for the 
Survival and Development of Mankind. He held informal meetings 
with Russian parliamentarians and Moscow officials and public 
figures, and took part in a seminar on global security and 
conflict settlement. 
  On Friday [20 May], the Dalai Lama attended an international 
prayer for peace which he served together with representatives 
of the Russian Orthodox, Islamic, Judaic and Buddhist clergy. 
  Kindness is the basis of human being and people of Russia 
must remember this, the Dalai Lama said. He called on the 
citizens of Russia to believe in themselves and not to abandon 
their hope for a better future. 
  The Dalai Lama said he was impressed by changes in Russia 
and 
the greater openness of society and people who eagerly joined in 
conversation with him in the street, asked questions and did not 
try to hide their opinion and emotions. 
  He believes Russia should come up with something new in the 
economic sphere in order to avoid the flaws of Western economies. 
  The Dalai Lama flew back to India today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

