<H3> <TI>   Position Clarified on Pakistan Holding Former POW's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Position Clarified on Pakistan Holding Former POW's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005165294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1422 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: By correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] On May 18, in Interfax's material concerning 
cooperation between Russian and Pakistani secret services in the 
efforts to free former Soviet prisoners of war published in News 
Bulletins and in Diplomatic Panorama, the press secretary of the 
director of Russia's Intelligence Service, Tatyana Samolis, was 
quoted as saying that former Soviet prisoners of war still 
remained in Pakistan. 
  In her Friday's interview with Interfax Samolis explained 
that some former Soviet servicemen taken prisoner "in the Afghan 
war" still remained abroad. 
  According to Samolis, she did not mean any concrete country, 
in particular Pakistan. 
  Members of Russia's Foreign Ministry explained to Interfax 
that former Soviet servicemen are held on Afghan soil. "Had our 
prisoners of war been in Pakistan, the Pakistanis would have 
extradited them long ago," a high-ranking Russian diplomat told 
Interfax's correspondent. 

</TEXT>

