<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Steps Taken To Ensure Security in Algeria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Steps Taken To Ensure Security in Algeria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005121894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1158 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Tyssovsky] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 20 TASS -- Director of the Middle East 
and Africa department of the Russian Foreign Ministry Viktor 
Posuvalyuk told ITAR-TASS by telephone today that the number of 
Russians in Algeria had substantially decreased during the 
recent period due to the evacuation of the wives and children of 
Russian specialists and employees of different organisations. 
Their total number now equals to 1,100 people. Various ways 
are being studied to ensure their security, including probable 
further reductions, he stressed. However, the recall of Russian 
experts from several sectors of the economy, which are vitally 
important for Algeria, is linked with definite difficulties, 
which may affect both friendly Algeria and Russia. 
  Touching on his Thursday meeting with Algerian ambassador to 
Moscow, Posuvalyuk explained that the demand to toughen security 
measures in order to protect Russian specialists, handed to the 
Algerian side, was "worded in the most resolute form". The 
sides also discussed ways to "approach the very concept of this 
security from a new angle, in particular, to lodge the Russians 
more compactly, which would make it easier for the Algerian law 
enforcement bodies to ensure their protection". 
  The ambassador stressed the difficulties with which the 
Algerian police was now confronted. It was decided to establish 
closer contacts of the Russian Embassy and the Algerian 
contractors with the local security services. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

