<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aid Convoy for Rwanda Refugees Flies to Tanzania </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aid Convoy for Rwanda Refugees Flies to Tanzania </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2005154494 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 21 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2005154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Marina Ryklina report: "Russian Convoy on African Soil"] </F>
  [Text] A special detachment from the Russian Ministry for 
Affairs of Civil Defense, Emergency Situations, and Elimination 
of Natural Disasters, comprising 15 drivers, communications 
workers, medics, and translators, flew out of Moscow to Tanzania 
18 May. Two transport aircraft -- an Il-76 and an An-124 
"Ruslan" -- delivered 10 "KamAZ" trucks, spares, and 
communications systems to the African continent. 
  According to figures from the World Food Program, there are 
already more than 320,000 refugees in Tanzania from neighboring 
Rwanda -- where an interethnic war still rages. Every day more 
than 1,500 people are arriving in the quest to escape. The 
United Nations is so far succeeding in supplying food to the 
world's largest refugee camp at Benako [name as transliterated]. 
  Within the framework of the recently concluded agreement to 
support the humanitarian aid operations, the Office of the UN 
High Commissioner for Refugees has appealed to its partner -- 
the Russian Ministry for Affairs of Civil Defense, Emergency 
Situations, and Elimination of Natural Disasters -- asking it to 
take part in transporting international humanitarian cargo to 
Rwandan refugee camps. Following this request an advance party 
from the Ministry for Affairs of Civil Defense, Emergency 
Situations, and Elimination of Natural Disasters went to 
Tanzania to arrange the routes for the delivery of the cargo and 
look at security problems, the conditions under which Russian 
drivers would be living, and funding issues. Our participation 
in this action will be effected on the basis of the United 
Nations reimbursing our transport costs, detachment members' 
pay, and certain other expenses.... 
  Meanwhile the Ministry for Affairs of Civil Defense, 
Emergency Situations, and Elimination of Natural Disasters is 
already installing a special communications system which will 
make it possible to monitor the Russian convoy's progress all 
along the route. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63383 </DOCNO>
