<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Firm Concludes Contracts To Build Ships in India </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Firm Concludes Contracts To Build Ships in India </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105091394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0651 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105091394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Alexey Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] New Delhi May 21 TASS -- A visit to India by Viktor 
Samoilov, managing director of Rosvooruzhenie, a state 
export-import company on weapons and combat materiel, ended on 
Saturday with signing several contracts on the construction in 
the republic of missile boats, frigates and escort ships. 
  He was received by Indian Minister of State for Defence M. 
Mallikarjun, had meetings with commanders of land, air and naval 
forces and visited shipyards in Bombay and Goa. 
  "The visit confirmed that Russian-Indian cooperation in the 
military and military-technical spheres has a long-term 
prospect," Samoilov said in an interview with ITAR-TASS. "We 
mapped out cooperation programmes for land, air and naval forces. 
  "A long-term plan has been drafted to build warships at 
Indian shipyards with Russian participation: over ten missile 
boats and some ten frigates and escort ships. One of them will 
be launched for running tests late this year." 
  Russia will supply all the main units, component parts and 
arms for these ships, he stressed. This means that new jobs 
will be created at Russian munitions factories. 
  Speaking about a Russian visit by Indian Premier P.V. 
Narasimha Rao and his talks with the Russian leaders, Samoilov 
said that the sides would discuss, among other things, military 
cooperation. 

</TEXT>

