<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Filatov Remarks on Shakhray </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Filatov Remarks on Shakhray </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105191594 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1700 GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105191594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Sergey Filatov, chief of President Yeltsin's </F>
staff, by correspondent Voskoboynikov; date and place not given] 
  [Text] [Voskoboynikov] Sergey Aleksandrovich, could it 
happen that you, like Sergey Shakhray, might have to find out 
from the newspapers about being removed from a official position? 
  [Filatov] Well, this is a difficult question. You see, I 
think it is a ridiculous thing that a person finds out from the 
newspapers or radio that a decree has been signed on his 
dismissal or removal, so to speak. The procedural system had 
not worked properly in this instance. Unfortunately, things 
like this do happen time from time. 
  [Voskoboynikov] Vyacheslav Kostikov, the Russian president's 
press secretary, said that Shakhray's plans were not always in 
line with Russia's real state interests. Nevertheless, 
President Yeltsin has decided to leave Shakhray in the position 
of Vice Premier. Why? 
  [Filatov] Well, you know, Shakhray's activities have been 
beneficial. Since the creation of the Russian Federation we 
have seen the important work he has been carrying out in one or 
another sector he has headed. That is why I think these 
circumstances were probably taken into account. Of course, his 
work is beneficial to the government and it is most likely that 
this was behind the president's decision to keep Shakhray. 

</TEXT>

