<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Discusses Dismissal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Discusses Dismissal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105202294 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1700 GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Sergey Shakhray, former Russian minister of </F>
nationalities and regional policy, by an unidentified 
correspondent; place and date not given; from the "Novosti" 
newscast -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Correspondent] Sergey Mikhaylovich, many people 
link your dismissal as minister for the affairs of nationalities 
and regional policy with your stand at the talks with Chechnya, 
and with the situation in the North Caucasus in general. Is 
that really the case? 
  [Shakhray] I do not think there is a direct link here. Even 
if there is, I still believe that decisions on personnel matters 
should be made by the prime minister and the president on their 
own, without prompts or recommendations from Chechen President 
Dzhokhar Dudayev, as some hinted was the case. I should like to 
say this is not a question of a certain personal stand of mine. 
There is a presidential message in which the policy toward 
Chechnya is formulated; there is a State Duma resolution. 
Therefore, I believe that all the federal bodies of state 
power--the Federation Council with its head, the State Duma, and 
the government--should act along the lines that have been 
defined, both in political and in legal terms, rather than 
conjure up some inventions of their own. After all, there 
should be elementary order in the country. 
  Incidentally, my resignation statement is connected with the 
breach of elementary procedures and order. On the one hand, I 
have been retained as a deputy prime minister in charge of the 
nationalities and regional policy, and on the other, a minister 
of whom I have not heard anything has been appointed to cover 
the same area. 
  [Correspondent] Do you foresee any more serious changes in 
the cabinet? 
  [Shakhray] I believe there will be no drastic upheavals and 
reshuffles. 
  [Correspondent] You mean, there will be no such proposal 
from 
the prime minister himself? 
  [Shakhray] You may have noticed that the prime minister, 
using his vast experience, believes that an old hand is better 
than two new ones. He prefers not to change his personnel, his 
ministers, as one changes one's gloves, but to work with the 
cadres he has. My personal feeling is that Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin will not allow any reshuffles in the 
government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

