<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communist Groups Call For Restoration of USSR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communist Groups Call For Restoration of USSR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205135494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1309 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Communist parties of the former Soviet republics are 
about to adjourn after a two-day closed-door conference at 
Gorkiy Leninskiye near Moscow. 
  Chairman Oleg Shenin of the Council of the Union of 
Communist 
parties -- the Communist Party of the Soviet Union told Interfax 
Communist parties of all the former Soviet republics, excluding 
Kazakhstan, attended the conference. Russia was represented by 
the Communist party of the Russian Federation (Gennadiy 
Zyuganov), the Communists' Union (Aleksey Prigarin) and the 
Russian Communist Workers' party whose delegation was led by 
First Secretary Viktor Tyulkin. The leader of the party's 
Moscow organization Viktor Anpilov took no part in the 
conference. 
  According to Shenin, the Communist parties exchanged views 
in 
a constructive and open spirit. They agreed the union of their 
republics must be restored and, Shenin said, they must 
coordinate action. 
  The conference discussed the possibility of holding a second 
congress of the peoples of the Soviet Union in the fall of 1994. 
The event would be expected to focus on the restoration of the 
unitary state. The conference is to close with decisions on the 
celebration of the 50th anniversary of the Soviet Union's 
victory in World War II and Lenin's 125th birthday anniversary. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63406 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_b_94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Seen Lukewarm About Forming United Movement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Seen Lukewarm About Forming United Movement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2005111594 Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY in Russian 20 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> MK2005111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Lev Sigal report in the "Opposition Is Looking for a </F>
Leader" column: "No Accord in the Name of Zorkin Is Working Out 
Yet"] 
  [Text] The Accord in the Name of Russia has so far failed 
to emerge as a powerful opposition super-movement. The founding 
conference of this organization, scheduled for Thursday, did not 
take place because organizational and technical preparations for 
it were not completed in time. As KOMMERSANT-DAILY predicted in 
its 13 May issue, the majority of opposition leaders today are 
not particularly interested in the accord. 
  The prospects for the Accord in the Name of Russia project 
still look uncertain. The movement initiators will apparently 
have to abandon their plans to encompass the entire opposition 
or at least a greater part of it. Ilya Kostantinov, the leader 
of the once notorious National Salvation Front, told 
KOMMERSANT-DAILY that he for one does not know anything about 
the organizational efforts by Mr. Zorkin and company and 
expressed doubt that the accord's founding conference will ever 
take place. 
  Apart from project coordinator Valeriy Zorkin, some activity 
toward the accord is being shown by Aleksandr Tsipko, Sergey 
Glazyev, Aman Tuleyev, and Petr Romanov. At the same time the 
initiative group has somewhat distanced itself from Aleksandr 
Rutskoy, who is now engaged with his own "Russian" organization, 
The State [Derzhava], as well as from Aleksandr Prokhanov. The 
initiators have shifted to the center somewhat and, unlike the 
ex- vice president, act on the assumption that the hopes for 
early presidential elections are unrealistic and therefore do 
not consider the question of presidential candidates. True, 
they say that Mr. Zorkin would like to see Aleksandr 
Solzhenitsyn as leader of the nation. 
  No doubt, the more time elapses between the emergence of the 
idea of the Accord and its structural organization, and the more 
stable the political situation in the country becomes, the 
farther the interests of the movement initiators are drifting 
apart. 
  Thus, observers point out that Gennadiy Zyuganov can now act 
independently. Aman Tuleyev and Petr Romanov are playing out a 
Siberian regional card; some other people would like to create a 
kind of industrial division of the Agrarian of Democratic Party. 
In this light, it is only "an opposition leaders club" whose 
formalization appears more or less realistic. Importantly, no 
one here possesses any substantial monetary resources; only 
communists and agrarians have human resources; and only Mr. 
Zorkin is trying to create an apparatus. So far, as movement 
cofounder Vasiliy Lipitskiy told KOMMERSANT-DAILY, a conference 
of movement supporters has been scheduled for 28 May which will 
apparently proclaim itself a National Council. The organizers 
hope for large and representative delegations to arrive from 
Siberia, Central Chernozem Region, and the South of Russia. 
Apparently the failure of the unification project will indicate 
that the crisis in the opposition has aggravated further. 
KOMMERSANT-DAILY will report on the conference results on 31 
May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63407 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_b_94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows 20 Percent Approve of Yeltsin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows 20 Percent Approve of Yeltsin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005164994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1434 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 20 TASS -- Twenty per cent of Russians 
surveyed said they approve of the work of President Yeltsin. 
About the same number had a good opinion of local authorities 
as well, according to a survey conducted by the "Public Opinion" 
fund among the country's urban and rural residents. 
  Answers to sociologists' questions concerning the future 
presidential elections revealed two tendencies. The first shows 
that, no matter who the presidential candidates are, from one 
fifth to one quarter of the respondents do not intend to vote. 
  The second trend shows that President Yeltsin still has the 
highest rating among possible candidates for the presidency. 
When asked to imagine that Yeltsin and Zhirinovskiy were the 
only candidates to pass the first round, 27 per cent of 
respondents said they would vote for Yeltsin, while 11 per cent 
favored the Liberal Democratic leader. In the same situation 
Yeltsin came out on top of former vice-president Aleksandr 
Rutskoy 21 to 11 per cent, and proved more popular than his 
current prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, 15 to 8 per cent. 
  The sociologists' inquiry was answered by, with differences 
according to the particular question, from 1139 to 2468 
respondents. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

