<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Safety Official on Unsafe Moscow Reactors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Safety Official on Unsafe Moscow Reactors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2005123194 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 20 May 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> MK2005123194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [INTERFAX report under the "In Brief" rubric"] </F>
  [Text] While there are currently more than 50 nuclear 
research plants in operation on the territory of Moscow, none of 
the working nuclear reactors have safety devices such as 
protective hoods, for example, measuring up to safety standards. 
Nevertheless, only three reactors have been shut down since 1992 
on the site of the Kurchatov Research Center, and they could be 
back in use again shortly. This has been advised by Vladimir 
Kuznetsov, chief of the Moscow inspectorate of the State 
Committee for the Supervision of Nuclear and Radiation Safety. 

</TEXT>

