<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kocharyan Describes Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kocharyan Describes Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105170894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1131 
GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Stepanakert, 21 May -- Robert Kocharyan, chairman 
of the State Committee for the Defence of Nagorno Karabakh, has 
said that the Nagorno Karabakh republic and the Crimean republic 
intend to "be persistent in implementing the accords reached". 
He told a news conference today about the results of the visit 
to the Crimean Peninsula by an official Nagorno Karabakh 
delegation. 
  A communique on the results of the meeting has been signed 
between the Nagorno Karabakh republic and the Crimean republic, 
as well as an agreement on trade and economic and cultural 
cooperation. 
  It is envisaged that there will be an exchange of 
representative offices and that privileges will be granted on 
transit freight and other things. On the political level, the 
sides came to agreement on coordinating actions, and also on 
possible joint steps in respect of a political settlement of the 
problems facing the two republics. Crimea's President Yuriy 
Meshkov may make a visit to Nagorno Karabakh in return. 
  Evaluating the current situation in Crimea, Robert Kocharyan 
commented that this was an attempt by the Ukrainian leadership 
to oppose any deepening of Crimean sovereignty. Karabakh has 
already passed this stage, and in Robert Kocharyan's view, this 
will have a consequence for Crimea and will only strengthen its 
sovereignty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

