<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Orders Patrols of Garrisons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Orders Patrols of Garrisons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205135894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1245 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi, 22 May -- Georgia's Defense Minister 
Lieutenant General Vardiko Nadibaidze issued instructions today 
on the introduction of military patrols in places where all six 
of the republic's military garrisons are deployed -- Tbilisi, 
Kutaisi, Rustavi, Akhaltsikhe, Telavi, and Gori. 
  This measure, adopted by the recent deputy commander of the 
Group of Russian Forces in the Caucasus, is aimed at preventing 
crimes by the rank and file and officer corps of the Georgian 
Army. 
  The situation as far as violations of the law is concerned 
is 
complicated by the fact that there are no legislative acts in 
Georgia regulating the ownership of short-barrelled weapons. 
Thus, citizens have free access to pistols and revolvers. 

</TEXT>

