<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aliyev Seeks Peace, Condemns Opposition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aliyev Seeks Peace, Condemns Opposition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205180994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1545 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205180994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Azerbaijani leadership seeks peace, Azerbaijani 
President Geydar Aliyev stated at a meeting with refugees from 
the Karabakh Region on Saturday. His address to the refugees 
was televised. 
  Aliyev said that the Azerbaijani leadership had been 
maintaining contacts with the CSCE and the Russian leaders in 
order to ensure permanent ceasefire and to eliminate the 
consequences of the Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict. 
  Aliyev commented on relations with the opposition and on its 
reaction to the Bishkek protocol. "The leadership made the right 
move having signed this protocol. For Baku it meant only 
ceasefire," he emphasized. 
  Aliyev condemned activities of the opposition deputies who 
had recently left the parliament and had organized a rally in 
Baku on Saturday. "Political parties should not act through 
rallies and mass actions of protest. They must consult the 
official bodies and interact with them," he pointed out. 
  Aliyev announced that people had been sending telegrams and 
calling from many Azerbaijani regions asking for an opportunity 
to come to Baku and to settle the accounts with the opposition. 
He said the fear of the opposition that Russian troops could be 
brought to Azerbaijan was in vain. "No Russian troops will be 
brought to Azerbaijan," Aliyev reassured. 
  Press Secretary of the National Independence opposition 
party 
(led by Etibar Mamedov) Rauf Mirgadyrov suggested in an 
interview with Interfax that after his statement Aliyev would 
have practically no chance to achieve any accord with the 
opposition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

