Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senior Aide Attacks Yeltsin Warning To Kravchuk </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Senior Aide Attacks Yeltsin Warning To Kravchuk </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105193194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1737 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A senior source in the Ukrainian president's staff 
has criticized Russian President Boris Yeltsin's comments on a 
telephone conversation he had on Friday with his Ukrainian 
counterpart, Leonid Kravchuk. 
  The comments, made in a television interview, "do not 
reflect 
the real content of the conversation," the source told 
INTERFAX-Ukraine. 
  He said Yeltsin's words that "the main thing is that neither 
Ukraine nor Russia should interfere in Crimean affairs" were 
"surprising." They suggested that Russia, in its relationship 
with Crimea, would like to have the same status as Ukraine, of 
which Crimea is part. 
  As for Yeltsin's statement that Ukraine must not use force 
against Crimea, the source said, "Ukraine is an independent 
state, and the methods it uses to solve its internal problems 
depend solely on the will of its people and parliament. 
Undoubtedly those methods would meet the Constitution and laws 
of Ukraine. Ukraine has observed and does observe international 
legal standards." 
  "What was also surprising was the rhetoric of the Russian 
president, who was speaking about the Ukrainian president in a 
disrespectful and admonishing manner," the source continued. 
  "The statement of the president of the Russian Federation 
would be much more constructive if he appealed to the 
separatists in the Republic of Crimea not to put in jeopardy 
peace in the region," the source summed up. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

