<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nation Willing To Transfer Bombers to Russia for High Price </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nation Willing To Transfer Bombers to Russia for High Price </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005103194 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 19 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2005103194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "To New Airfields?"] </F>
  [Text] Ukraine expressed its readiness to transfer to 
Russia nationalized strategic bombers -- but for a lot of money. 
The Defense Ministry of the Russian Federation believes that 
our state presently has 42 heavy bombers at its disposal, while 
the Russian Air Force has 77 such machines. The Russian Army 
finds it difficult to deploy new aircraft because the financing 
of their serial production has been halted. As a result, in 
accordance with the plans by the Russian Federation's Ministry 
of Defense, the Air Force will remain without changes until the 
year 2000. "If Ukraine does not agree to our terms, the 
aircraft will remain on its territory," stated a representative 
of the Russian Federation's Ministry of Defense. This was 
reported by the information agency ITAR-TASS. 

</TEXT>

