<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Official: Kravchuk Needs Crisis To Stop Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Official: Kravchuk Needs Crisis To Stop Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205175394 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1500 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Passions have been running high lately in the 
Crimea, but today the situation is somewhat less tense. Very 
probably this is because talks are going to take place tomorrow 
between the government delegations of Russia and Ukraine 
concerning the situation on the peninsula. It will be recalled 
that Kiev's delegation will be led by Yuhym Zvyahilskyy, the 
acting prime minister. What results does Simferopol expect of 
this meeting? Our correspondent is talking to Vyacheslav 
Lebedev, the press secretary of the Crimean president. 
  [Begin Lebedev recording] The negotiating process has begun, 
and both Russia and Ukraine realize there is a need for talks, 
so the results are bound to come -- not at once, perhaps, but 
there will be results. The very fact talks are taking place 
will have a positive influence on developments in the Crimea. 
As for the situation in the Crimea, the president is in control 
-- that is, of the things he can control. He cannot, for 
example, control the fleet, and the troops are also being 
controlled by someone different. [end recording] 
  If the representatives of Russia and Ukraine discuss the 
situation in the Crimea tomorrow, then talks between the 
parliamentary delegations of Simferopol and Kiev will take place 
on 24 May. [passage omitted] And what is the current situation 
like? Once more, here is the press secretary of the Crimean 
president: 
  [Begin Lebedev recording] The situation is normal and quiet. 
The tension exists only on the top level and is largely 
internal. We realize the presidential election in Ukraine is 
scheduled for 26 June and Kravchuk is making his last attempts 
to play the Crimean card and disrupt the election or put some 
sort of pressure on the deputies. We shall try to defend 
ourselves and not give him a pretext to introduce a state of 
emergency and thus avoid the election. It is by this that the 
present situation has been caused and these difficulties are 
mainly temporary. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

