<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Politicians Blame Kravchuk for Crimea Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Politicians Blame Kravchuk for Crimea Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305050794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0408 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305050794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Melnik] </F>
  [Text] Kiev, 23 May (TASS) -- Some politicians in Ukraine 
have been blaming President Leonid Kravchuk for the situation, 
which has taken shape in the Crimea. Sergey Golovaty, for one, 
said during his appearance on national television on Sunday that 
"the president of Ukraine has shown indecision with regard to 
the leadership of the autonomous republic. We are now in a 
state where Leonid Kravchuk is no longer able to do anything 
because he is three years late. Any actions of his can now 
exacerbate the situation even more." 
  Sergey Golovaty said the only way out of the situation 
consists in "bringing all the latest decrees and resolutions of 
the parliament and the president of the Crimea in line with 
Ukraine's legislation." 
  Former vice-premier, Igor Yukhnovsky, stressed that "Ukraine 
cannot do without the Crimea and will do everything possible to 
preserve its territorial integrity." Some other parliament 
members called for direct presidential rule in the Crimea. 

</TEXT>

