<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saburov Blames Crimean Crisis on Kravchuk Not Ukraine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saburov Blames Crimean Crisis on Kravchuk Not Ukraine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005160794 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1500 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Thirty minutes ago we made contact with Yevgeniy 
Saburov, the Crimean head of government, to get his views on 
what is going on in Simferopol. 
  [Begin Saburov recording] The reaction by Kravchuk was 
completely uncalled for. When you ask for the law to be 
observed, you cannot then introduce a state of emergency. That 
is true, unless you have some ulterior motives, so to speak. As 
for ulterior motives, I do not know who thinks they are 
ulterior. They are all out in the open, completely open to view. 
  Here we are talking about the Ukrainian presidential 
election. Everything that is happening in Crimea is linked to 
this issue alone. It is the only way for Leonid Makarevich 
Kravchuk to call off the presidential election. Therefore, 
strictly speaking, it will be completely inaccurate to talk 
about Ukraine here. Here we should be talking about a number of 
characters in the Kiev leadership who are prepared to risk a lot 
in pursuit of their own goals. 
  So, how far are they prepared to go? This, incidentally, is 
a matter for their consciences. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

