<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimea Given 10-Day Ultimatum To Drop Constitution Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimea Given 10-Day Ultimatum To Drop Constitution Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005174694 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1700 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by correspondent Murtazin; from the "Novosti" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Today, Leonid Kravchuk held a meeting to discuss the 
political situation in Crimea. The president of Ukraine intends 
to cancel the decision taken by the Crimean Supreme Soviet to 
restore the Crimean Constitution of 6 May 1992, according to 
which legal relations between Ukraine and Crimea are on a treaty 
basis and the people of Crimea have the right to dual 
citizenship. Earlier on television, Kravchuk announced that he 
will act decisively and consistently within the Constitution to 
protect Ukraine's territorial integrity. 
  At the same time, in Kiev, the republic's Supreme Council is 
meeting behind closed doors and the president is expected to 
speak. He intends to persuade the deputies to cancel the verdict 
by the Crimean Supreme Council and will most likely get approval 
for introducing a regime of special rule in Crimea. 
  [Announcer Nelli Petkova] Our correspondent has just 
reported 
that Ukraine's Supreme Council has adopted the following 
decision: To recommend that Crimea's Supreme Soviet reexamine 
and cancel its constitutional decision. If it fails to do so, 
in 10 days a decision by the Ukraine's Supreme Council on 
suspending the acts in question adopted by the Crimean 
parliament will automatically come into force. This decision 
was made at about 2000 Moscow time. 
  The deputies then started to set up a special deputies' 
commission, which, along with people's deputies from Crimea, 
will go to Simferopol to settle all these problems. 

</TEXT>

