<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies Say Constitution Does Not Mean Crimea's Secession </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputies Say Constitution Does Not Mean Crimea's Secession </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2005112294 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 1000 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2005112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Presidium of the Sixth Crimean Supreme Council 
today adopted a law of the Crimean Republic on restoring the 
constitutional foundations of the Crimean Republic's statehood. 
Thus, the fundamental law of the Crimean Republic from 6 May 
1992 was restored on the territory of the peninsula. 
  In this way, the deputies ignored an appeal by Ukrainian 
President Leonid Kravchuk, asking them not to take such a 
dangerous step aimed at encroaching upon Ukraine's territorial 
integrity. (?As early as yesterday), Crimean President Meshkov 
asked the deputies to temporarily suspend the debate on this 
issue. Deputies, however, did not listen. 
  Arguments in favor of restoring the constitution in its 
previous form were voiced at the session, mainly referring to 
the Crimean people's [word indistinct] and will expressed during 
a presidential poll. It was emphasized that a return to the 
previous constitution does not mean Crimea's secession from 
Ukraine. Article (?11) of the constitution from 6 May 1992 
states that the Crimean Republic is a part of Ukraine, and that 
its relations with Ukraine are based on agreements and treaties. 
The law of the Crimean Republic on restoring the constitutional 
foundations of the Crimean Republic's statehood was adopted 
without including it on the agenda; 69 out of 83 deputies 
present at the session voted for adopting it. The session also 
appointed a delegation for talks with the Ukrainian Supreme 
Council. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

