<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Communist Leader on Constitution Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Communist Leader on Constitution Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005213594 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 2100 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005213594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sevastopol, 20 May -- Leonid Hrach, head of the 
Communist Party of Crimea, commenting on today's decision by the 
Crimean Supreme Council to renew the operation of the autonomy's 
Constitution in its 1992 form, called on the parliamentarians to 
stop and not to let the decision, which was adopted, provoke a 
military conflict in the Crimea. "If blood is spilled in the 
Crimea, we will not be able to talk about conducting any kind of 
reforms," he emphasized. Mr. Hrach addressed a proposal to 
Yuriy Meshkov, the president of the autonomy, to begin talks and 
consultations with Ukraine's leadership. 
  Incidentally, 69 out of 73 deputies (there are 98 deputies 
in 
Crimea's Supreme Council) voted to renew the Constitution of 
Crimea in its 1992 form. The group of Crimean Tatars (14 
persons) refused to take part in the voting. 
  The statement by the Crimean Supreme Council's press center, 
which was disseminated today, says that the inclusion of this 
issue on the session's agenda had been done "at the will of the 
people of Crimea." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

