<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kiev Denies Sending Armored Vehicles </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kiev Denies Sending Armored Vehicles </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205205994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2048 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205205994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow/Kiev 22 May TASS -- The situation on the 
Crimean Peninsula remains rather tense. According to a 
spokesman for the Crimean president, 29 Ukrainian armoured 
personnel vehicles entered the regional capital Simferopol on 
Sunday [22 May] night. With this in view, the Crimean Interior 
Ministry reinforced its units securing key government buildings, 
including the main broadcasting centre and parliament 
headquarters, the spokesman reported. 
  According to reliable military sources, the armoured 
vehicles 
brought by railway are now deployed at the station of Simferopol. 
  The Black Sea Fleet's combat units are staying at their 
usual 
locations, a spokesman for the fleet's headquarters told TASS. 
Because of the volatile situation in the Crimea, the fleet 
reinforced the guard of its installations, but there are no 
manoeuvres or redeployment. 
  Meanwhile, in an interview with national television on 
Sunday 
night, Ukraine's First Deputy Interior Minister Valentin 
Nedrigailo denied reports about sending Ukrainian armoured 
personnel vehicles to Simferopol. According to him, the 
situation in the Crimea and Ukraine is quite calm. 

</TEXT>

