<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Official Denies Impending Clashes in Simferopol </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interior Official Denies Impending Clashes in Simferopol </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305125994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1104 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] First Deputy Ukrainian Interior Minister Valentin 
Nedrigailo called allegations of an impending armed 
confrontation in Simferopol as a stupid statement. He told 
INTERFAX-Ukraine on Sunday [22 May] evening that people were 
walking across the city and nothing was happening. "This is a 
state of illness" when one imagines intervention and troops in 
the streets, he remarked. 
  Nedrigailo pointed out that there had been complete mutual 
understanding and confidence between the Ukrainian and the 
Crimean interior ministries. He added that the Ukrainian 
National Guard units were carrying out their law enforcement 
duties together with Crimean police officers. 
  Commenting on the information concerning Ukrainian armored 
vehicles in Simferopol, Nedrigailo said their arrival in 
Simferopol had been made known long ago. First Deputy Crimean 
Parliament Chairman Viktor Mezhak and a group of Crimean 
parliamentarians had been present when the armored vehicles 
arrived on Saturday. 
  Nedrigailo announced that about twenty armored vehicles had 
come. Non-official sources said that there had been about 29 
armored vehicles arriving in Simferopol. 
  It is just normal equipment of the National Guards with 
armored carriers, Nedrigailo emphasized. 

</TEXT>

