<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Leader Praises Council on Restoring Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Leader Praises Council on Restoring Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105132494 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1130 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Kiev, [no dateline as received] -- At the 
Crimean Supreme Council's plenary sitting on 21 May, Crimean 
President Yuriy Meshkov congratulated the deputies on the 
adoption of the Crimean law "On restoring the constitutional 
basis of the Republic of Crimea's statehood" and declared that 
the constitution he had sworn allegiance to was that adopted on 
6 May 1992. 
  Yuriy Meshkov gave an account of his tour of Krasnodar on 20 
May, where he took part in the work of the Association of 
Socio-Economic Cooperation between North Caucasian republics, 
krays, and oblasts. At the association's sitting in Krasnodar, 
Crimea was admitted to this North Caucasian organization as an 
associate member. In Yuriy Meshkov's words, preparations for 
Crimea's entry into the association had been under way for six 
months, especially since his election as president. During his 
stay in Krasnodar, the Crimean president also took part in the 
work of the Grand Assembly of Cossack Host Atamans and met 
representatives of the Krasnodar kray public. [passage omitted] 
  Crimean Supreme Council Deputy Viktor Mezhak informed the 
deputies that, under the accord of 21 May with the head of the 
Supreme Council of Ukraine Secretariat, a Crimean Supreme 
Council delegation, to be led by Crimean parliamentary speaker 
Serhiy Tsekov, would meet a Ukrainian Supreme Council 
delegation, to be led by Borys Oliynyk, in Kiev next week. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

