<H3> <TI>   Crimean Legislature Ready for Talks With Kiev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Legislature Ready for Talks With Kiev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105164094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1244 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2105164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Crimean legislature is ready to hold talks with 
Ukraine's parliament, but it will not accept conditions set by 
Kiev, the head of the Russia parliamentary faction, Sergey 
Nikulin, who leads the parliamentary commission on legislation, 
law, order and national development, told Interfax-Ukraina on 
Saturday [21 May]. 
  A Crimean parliamentary delegation led by the Speaker, 
Sergey 
Tsekov, is expected to meet with a Ukrainian parliamentary 
delegation in Kiev on Tuesday. 
  As we already reported, on Friday Ukraine's parliament urged 
the Crimean parliament to cancel its Thursday's resolution 
issued to revert to the Crimean Constitution adopted on 6 May 
1992. 
  Besides, Ukraine's parliament suspended the bill adopted to 
restore the Crimean Constitution of 6 May 1992. Under that 
Constitution all relations between the Crimea and Ukraine are 
built on the basis of agreement, and the people of the Crimea 
are entitled to "dual citizenship." 
  Ukraine's parliament adopted a resolution suggesting that 
the 
Crimean parliament should annul its decision within 10 days. 

</TEXT>

