<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Appeals to UN, Russia, People of Ukraine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Appeals to UN, Russia, People of Ukraine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105134294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1312 
GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik; all quotation marks as received] 
  [Text] Kiev, 21 May -- "The leadership of Ukraine has 
taken a series of measures aimed at destroying the statehood of 
the Republic of Crimea. It threatens to use force, including 
military force," says an appeal of the Supreme Council of the 
Republic of Crimea, which was adopted today. It is addressed to 
the United Nations, the UN Security Council, the Conference for 
Security and Cooperation in Europe, the president of the Russian 
Federation, the Russian Federal Assembly, and the people of 
Ukraine. 
  The document says, among other things, that "the Crimean 
Supreme Council adopted the law on restoring the constitutional 
foundations of the statehood of the Republic of Crimea on the 
basis of a poll taken among the Republic's citizens. This means 
that from now on the authority in economy, education, culture, 
and local self-government will be executed entirely by the 
people of Crimea." 
  The Crimean parliamentarians think that "not a single item 
in 
the Constitution of the Crimean Republic infringes upon the 
territorial integrity of the Ukraine, nor does it lead to any 
revision of the existing state border. Chapter 3, Article 9 of 
the Constitution states: "The Crimean Republic forms part of 
Ukrainian and determines its relations with that state on the 
basis of a treaty and agreements." The Crimean Supreme Council 
confirms its adherence to the principles enshrined in the 
Helsinki Final Act of the Conference on Security and Cooperation 
in Europe. 
  The Crimean Supreme Council expressed the hope that the 
international community will not permit lawless acts on the part 
of Ukraine's organs of state power nor any violation of the 
rights and freedoms proclaimed by the "Universal Declaration of 
the Rights of Man." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

