<DOCNO> FBIS4-63505 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_f_94044" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supreme Council Resolution on Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Supreme Council Resolution on Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2105172494 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1500 GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2105172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukraine's Supreme Council has adopted a resolution 
on halting the operation of the law of the Republic of Crimea on 
renewing the constitutional basis of the Republic of Crimea's 
statehood: 
  On 20 May 1994, the Republic of Crimea's Supreme Council 
adopted a law on renewing the constitutional basis of the 
Republic of Crimea's statehood, which renews clauses of the 
Republic of Crimea's Constitution in its 6 May 1992 form. These 
clauses in the Constitution were changed in September 1992 by 
the Republic of Crimea's Supreme Council itself in accordance 
with the law of Ukraine on the delimitation of powers between 
the state authority bodies of Ukraine and the Republic of Crimea. 
  Above all, it is about establishing relations between the 
Crimea and Ukraine on the basis of treaties and agreements and 
about introducing Crimean citizenship. This is a step toward 
Crimea leaving the composition of Ukraine, which violates the 
territorial integrity of Ukraine and its state sovereignty, and 
runs counter to the universally recognized principles of 
international law. 
  In accordance with Article 75 of Ukraine's Constitution, the 
Crimean Autonomous Republic is a constituent part of Ukraine and 
can resolve independently only those issues attributed to its 
authority. The competence of state authority bodies of the 
Republic of Crimea is determined by the above-mentioned law of 
Ukraine on the delimitation of powers between the state bodies 
of Ukraine and the Republic of Crimea. In accordance with 
Article 11 of this law, the higher bodies of state authority of 
the Republic of Crimea do not have the right to resolve issues 
belonging to the exclusive authority of the state bodies of 
Ukraine. The extent of the powers of the Republic of Crimea, in 
accordance with Ukraine's legislation, cannot be changed by the 
Republic of Crimea without the consent of Ukraine's Supreme 
Council. 
  Taking account of the above, and with the aim of protecting 
state sovereignty and ensuring the supremacy of the laws of 
Ukraine on all of its territory, and in accordance with Point 31 
of Article 97 of the Constitution of Ukraine, Ukraine's Supreme 
Council resolves: 
  1. To halt the operation of the law of the Republic of 
Crimea 
of 20 May 1994 on renewing the constitutional basis of the 
Republic of Crimea's statehood as such that runs counters to the 
Declaration on Ukraine's State Sovereignty, the demands of 
Articles 31, 70, 75, and 77 of the Constitution of Ukraine, and 
the laws of Ukraine on the delimitation of powers between the 
state authority bodies of Ukraine and the Republic of Crimea and 
on citizenship of Ukraine; 
  2. To propose that the Republic of Crimea's Supreme Council 
brings the Republic of Crimea's Constitution into line with the 
Constitution of Ukraine and the laws of Ukraine on the 
delimitation of powers between the bodies of state authority of 
Ukraine and the Republic of Crimea within 10 days. 
  3. That this resolution loses its validity from the moment 
when the Supreme Council of the Republic of Crimea revokes the 
law on renewing the constitutional basis of the Republic of 
Crimea's statehood. 
  You have been listening to Ukraine's Supreme Council 
resolution on halting the operation of the law of the Republic 
of Crimea on renewing the constitutional basis of the Republic 
of Crimea's statehood. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

