Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukrainian Railways Not Asked To Move Troops Toward Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukrainian Railways Not Asked To Move Troops Toward Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205161194 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1500 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In connection with reports by Russian mass media 
about the supposed redeployment of Ukrainian military units and 
formations in the direction of the Autonomous Republic of 
Crimea, the press service of Ukrzaliznytsya [Ukrainian Railways] 
made a statement on 22 May. In particular, it says that over 
the last 10 days Ukrzaliznytsya has not received or examined any 
requests from the Defense Ministry or the National Guard of 
Ukraine to move military cargoes, personnel, or military 
equipment in the direction of the Crimea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63514 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_f_94053" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Internal Affairs Ministry Calls on Crimea To Obey Kiev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Internal Affairs Ministry Calls on Crimea To Obey Kiev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205175994 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1600 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Today, the board of Ukraine's Internal Affairs 
Ministry held an extended meeting. It examined the situation in 
the Republic of Crimea and adopted an appeal to the Supreme 
Council and president of the Crimean Republic, as well as the 
board's appeal to the interior bodies' personnel. It says, in 
particular, that a dangerous precedent was set for ignoring the 
laws of the Ukrainian state, which is having a negative effect 
on the functioning of interior bodies in Crimea and, first of 
all, the state of law and order. An explosive situation is 
being provoked and mounted, suspicion and mistrust for the 
Ukrainian authorities is being planted. 
  The board of Ukraine's Internal Affairs Ministry is placing 
all responsibility for the current developments in Crimea and 
the possible unforseen consequences on Mr. Valeriy Kuznetsov, 
appointed to the abolished post of the Crimean internal affairs 
minister, and the forces that had created conditions for this. 
  Appealing to the Supreme Council and president of the 
Republic of Crimea, the board of Ukraine's Internal Affairs 
Ministry is counting on them to exercise foresight, wisdom, and 
consideration in their decisions concerning issues that relate 
to the functioning of such an important armed formation as 
interior bodies. The appeal also contains an expression of 
confidence that the Crimean leadership will revise their earlier 
decisions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
